<DOCNO> AP890904-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 0019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-DrugWar-Farmers     09-04 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug War-Farmers,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Will South American Farmers Switch from Coca to Coffee?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. drug officials are concerned that a
disruption of cocaine production in Colombia because of the
government crackdown will raise cocaine prices in Peru and Bolivia
and make it harder to persuade farmers to switch from coca leaf to
other crops.
   An estimated 300,000 people in Bolivia depend on coca farming and
cocaine production for a livelihood. Coca leaf still provides a 100
percent profit to farmers and coca-leaf acreage increased by 20
percent in 1987-88, according to a U.S. State Department report.
   For farmers to stop growing coca leaves, viable alternative crops
must be found. But with the recent drop in the price of coffee _ a
crop suited for the tropics where coca is grown _ and the lack of
other profitable alternative crops, farmers prefer to grow coca,
which provides four crops a year and is easy to sell.
   The Bolivian government last year passed a law that limits
coca-leaf acreage. President Jaime Paz Zamora's government, which
was sworn in Aug. 6, says it will wage an all-out war against
traffickers.
   Coca-leaf reduction in Bolivia is moving ahead but slowly as the
new government implements an anti-drug strategy.
   Bolivian law calls for the reduction of 12,350 acres of coca land
by the end of the year in order to comply with a quota agreed upon
by the U.S. government. If the quota is not reached Bolivia stands
to loose $10 million in aid. This year so far only about 3,200 acres
have been destroyed.
   In Peru, coca leaf reduction programs in the 150-mile Huallaga
Valley, 300 miles northeast of Lima, have been temporarily suspended
because of threats to U.S. drug agents and the killing of Peruvian
officials.
   Coca farmers and traffickers in Peru have allied themselves with
insurgency groups, among them the Shining Path, and many coca-leaf
producing areas are off limits to law enforcement officials.
Eradiction and interdiction activities in the Huallaga Valley are
expected to resume this month when a secure base is completed in the
Santa Lucia area.
   Peru destroyed 12,670 acres of coca in just four months last year.
   Peru produces coca leaves on 285,600 acres. It is the main
supplier of paste for Colombian cocaine producers and distributors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890904-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 0020EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Militia     09-04 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Militia,0835</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Militia Caught Between Resentment and Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The old man smoothes his blue uniform
shirt and snaps to attention as a visitor approaches the
fortress-like Workers' Militia headquarters.
   Asked how long he has been a militiaman, Jozsef Szerepi smiles
broadly. ``Since the beginning,'' he says.
   Established by the Communists as the ``Iron Fist of the Party'' a
year after Soviet tanks crushed the 1956 Hungarian revolution, the
militia was for years the pride of the men who fought to defend
communism.
   But as Hungary prepares for the first free parliamentary
elections since the Communists consolidated power in 1947, the
militia is under orders from the Communist Party to transform itself
into an apolitical force.
   Political opposition groups question whether it can do so,
warning darkly that the 60,000-member militia could take to the
streets to keep the Communists in power should they lose in the June
elections.
   On the other side of the ideological spectrum, some hard-line
Communist militiamen complain bitterly of being betrayed, both by
the party and by their organization.
   Although the organization makes much of its role in providing
emergency help in floods, fires and other natural calamities, it
remains identified with the Soviet submachine gun that forms the
centerpiece of its emblem.
   A May survey of 700 Hungarians showed that between 77 percent and
84 percent of those polled favored the militia's dissolution.
   After endorsing the concept of multi-party democracy earlier this
year, the Hungarian Communist Party announced May 8 that it no
longer would control the militia.
   Militia officials say they are trying to reorganize into a force
that would take orders only from the government _ even a future
non-Communist government. But it's a daunting task.
   For more than three decades, militiamen have been required to
swear allegiance to ``the red flag of the international workers'
class,'' and to be prepared to give their lives to protect ``the
rule of the working class.''
   Militia spokesman Andras Zelenak acknowledged rank-and-file
discontent with Hungary's reform course, saying, ``Some members of
the Workers' Militia are stunned about what is going on in this
country.''
   Militiaman Ferenc Goenczoel agreed during an interview at
Zelenak's office, where busts of Lenin shared shelf space with books
on Marxist ideology.
   ``It is difficult to digest these great and quick changes,
because much is contrary to the ideological philosopy that we
brought with us,'' Goenczoel said. ``I cannot make an about face
from one day to the next.''
   Goenczoel, who said he had been a militiaman for more than two
decades, said disappointment in Hungary's present political course
is greatest among working class comrades-in-arms and those who
fought alongside Soviet troops in 1956.
   ``The older ones are most bitter _ even about the party, that it
left the Workers' Militia in the lurch,'' said Goenczoel.
   Many members felt most betrayed by the Communist leadership's
decision in February to abandon the 32-year terminology describing
the 1956 revolt. What officially had been a traitorous
counter-revolution suddenly became a popular uprising.
   Then, the leadership rehabilitated the revolution's leaders and
conducted their ceremonial reburial June 16, more than 30 years
after their execution as traitors.
   ``There was an outcry,'' Goenczoel said. ``It was most difficult
for the older members who fought on the barricades'' in 1956, he
said.
   Zelenak said some embittered members of the largely volunteer
force have resigned rather than accept the changes, but asserted the
militia could adapt to an emerging democracy.
   But anti-Communist political groups demanding abolition of the
Workers' Militia in pre-election negotiations with the Communists
are skeptical, saying the armed forces should be the only ones to
have weapons.
   Some even see parallels to Hitler's stormtroopers, who helped the
Nazi dictator to power.
   ``This Workers' Militia is a little bit like the stormtroopers in
Germany, a symbol of the totalitarian system,'' said opposition
figure Csaba Kiss.
   Kiss, spokesman of the Hungarian Democratic Forum, suggested that
Hungarian Communists could ``be waiting for the right moment'' _ a
conservative turn away from reform in the Soviet Union. The Workers'
Militia then could ``become the base for a reactionary turn at
home,'' he said.
   Militia members vehemently deny they would ever act against the
popular will or the legal government, although some radicals outside
the organization say they do not exclude the possibility of armed
insurrection to keep the Communists in power.
   Announcing the formation of a Marxist-Leninist Party Aug. 25,
self-styled spokesman Sandor Petres told the newspaper Mai Nap his
organization would not hesitate ``to seize weapons'' if the
elections exclude the working class from Parliament.
   Most analysts made light of his remarks and of his organization.
But the army apparently attached enough importance to the comments
to issue a statement expressing support of peaceful political change
in Hungary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
