<FIRST>r a PM-Names     09-04 0911</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles has renewed his attacks on soulless
modern buildings, writing that architects are creating
Frankenstein's monsters.
   The fashionable architectural theories of the 1950s and 1960s
have spawned ``deformed monsters which have come to haunt our towns
and cities, our villages and our countryside,'' the prince said in
``A Vision of Britain,'' as excerpted in the Sunday Times.
   The 40-year-old heir to the British throne has harshly criticized
modern buildings that he believes fail to meet the needs of the
people who must live and work in them.
   ``As a result of 30 years of experimenting with revolutionary
building materials and novel ideas, burning all the rulebooks and
purveying the theory that man is a machine, we have ended up with
Frankenstein monsters, devoid of character, alien and largely
unloved, except by the professors who have been concocting these
horrors in their laboratories _ and even they find their creations a
bit hard to take after a while,'' the excerpt said.
   The book is to be published in Britain on Thursday by Doubleday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Who is winding up its 25th anniversary tour on
a harmonious note for a change, singer Roger Daltrey says.
   ``We've ended up friends, which is great for us. That's a real
triumph. It was not a happy ending in 1982, but it feels great
now,'' Daltrey said of the rock group, whose members have argued and
brawled through the years.
   The Who's performance Saturday was the finale to a day-long party
at the Astrodome sponsored by Miller beer. The band played Sunday
night at a similar party in Dallas, drawing 45,000 people to the
72,000-capacity Cotton Bowl on a hot, humid day.
   At a preconcert news conference Saturday with band members and
party pitchman Randy Quaid, Daltrey dismissed criticism of the
association of beer parties with charity. Miller has committed $1
million from the parties' proceeds to the Texas Special Olympics.
   ``As long as we're raising money for charity, we'd consider
anything. That's the main reason we're here,'' he said.
   A Special Olympics participant, 31-year-old Kevin Maples,
presented Quaid and The Who with gold medals he won in competition.
Who guitarist and songwriter Pete Townshend gave Maples an electric
guitar autographed by the group members.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donna Douglas, known for her love of
``critters'' as Elly May Clampett on ``The Beverly Hillbillies,'' is
marketing a line of cologne for her four-footed friends.
   ``I travel too much to have a pet at home in Los Angeles, but
down home I have dogs, chickens and cows,'' Ms. Douglas, of Baywood,
La., said on a recent trip to Nashville.
   Her Critter Country Classics Pet Cologne includes a ``Miss
Tabby'' scent for cats and ``Timber Wolf'' for dogs.
   She also has made a double album _ one disc country, the other
gospel _ and is selling a limited-edition Elly May porcelain doll.
But there are no plans for the simple country millionaires, who
appeared on network television from 1961-72 to reunite, she said.
   ``Awhile back, there had been some talk of a ``Hillbillies''
reunion TV movie, but Maxie Baer (Jethro) didn't want to do it,''
Ms. Douglas said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Version moving on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though nearing retirement at age 34, tennis star
Chris Evert was able to wear down a 15-year-old opponent to reach
the quarterfinals of the U.S. Open for the 19th straight year.
   Evert, a six-time winner of the tournament who says this is her
last Open, sent Monica Seles chasing balls from corner to corner
Sunday in rallies that sometimes lasted more than 50 shots, and won
6-0, 6-2.
   ``I don't know where it came from,'' Evert said. ``I haven't seen
that form all year.''
   Martina Navratilova said she knew the fourth-seeded Evert, her
longtime friend and rival, would be ``totally psyched'' to beat
12th-seeded Seles.
   ``I knew she was not going to lose to Seles today,'' Navratilova
said. ``It's nothing against Monica, she's a nice girl, but I knew
she would not lose to a youngster like that in a round like that.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Zsa Zsa Gabor, preparing for trial
next week on charges she slapped a policeman, has selected her
courtroom outfit: a black Valentino designer dress, black hat and
pearls.
   Miss Gabor claims the Beverly Hills motorcycle officer roughed
her up June 14 after stopping her Rolls-Royce convertible.
   ``I tell you mainly why I go to trial: that this shouldn't happen
to other women,'' Miss Gabor said during an interview last week at
her Bel-Air mansion.
   ``They wanted to drop all the charges. And the funny part is they
wanted to make, how do you call, civic work for 100 hours. And this
guy (Rob Lowe) who had pornographic movies, he only got 20 hours''
of community service.
   Miss Gabor is charged with battery on a policeman, disobeying an
officer, driving with an expired license, having an open container
of alcohol in her car and having expired car registration. If
convicted, she could be sentenced to two years in prison.
   Miss Gabor, a former Miss Hungary, is married to her eighth
husband, Prince Frederick von Anhalt, Germany's Duke of Saxony. In
addition to her movie roles, she has written two books about men and
started cosmetics and jewelry businesses. In October, she will star
as the owner of an animal beauty parlor in ``Animal Haven.''
</TEXT>
