<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 8thLd-Writethru a0780 09-04 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0780,0806</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>First Planes Arrive From U.S.; President Fires Anti-Drug Chief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with bomb damaging four business,
wounding three people outside Medellin. Pickup 2nd pvs, `Also Sunday...'</HEAD>
<UNK>By BRUCE HANDLER ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two U.S. C-130 transport planes flew into
Bogota Sunday, marking the beginning of the delivery of $65 million
in U.S. military aid to combat drug traffickers.
   An explosion ripped through four businesses near the cocaine
capital of Medellin Sunday night, wounding at least three people,
the Colombian radio network RCN said.
   The bomb in Itagui, just south of Medellin, damaged a bank, an
insurance company's office, a shoe store and an optical shop, an
Itagui police spokesman told the Associated Press in a telephone
interview. The spokesman asked to remain anonymous.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the bombing, but it
followed the method of terror that drug traffickers have employed in
Medellin where they have set off bombs at banks and other businesses.
   Two small bombs exploded Sunday night in front of the
Intercontinental Hotel in Medellin but no one was hurt, police said.
   Also Sunday, President Virigilo Barco replaced the chief of the
anti-drug effort in Medellin. A source said he was ousted for having
dealings with drug lords but officials denied such reports.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas McNamara, at the Bogota military air base
where the C130s landed, said the planes ``are in excellent condition
and should serve the Colombian armed forces for many years.''
   The commander of Colombia's air force, Gen. Alfonso Amaya
Maldonado, said the C-130s ``will be used in the fight in which we
are engaged ... to re-establish order.''
   In Washington, White House Chief of Staff John Sununu told CBS'
``Face the Nation'' that if Colombia requests more assistance,
President Bush probably would order American troops to take an
active role in fighting Colombia's drug lords.
   McNamara said the transport planes, from National Guard bases in
Louisville, Ky., and Martinsburg, W. Va., brought spare parts for
eight A-37 observation and attack aircraft the United States expects
to deliver Monday in the Caribbean port of Barranquilla.
   Three American crewmen, all dressed in olive-green flight suits,
disembarked from each plane.
   An AP photographer who peered through the opened tailgate of one
of the C-130s said it contained large crates covered by plastic and
nets.
   Five UH-1H transport helicopters are to arrive Tuesday, the
ambassador said.
   Washington has said as many as 200 American military personnel
may come to Colombia to assist security forces in installing and
operating the American equipment. This is a potential sore point, as
Colombian officials have said they don't want American troops.
   McNamara told reporters, ``Right now I don't have an exact
number'' of American advisers in Colombia but it is ``very few.''
   ``Coming in ... will be a few ground crews to handle the
aircraft. These crews will be here for a few hours or days,'' he
said. ``We will have a few trainers come in and assist with the
transfer of the equipment and the training'' of Colombians.
   The United States also has promised Colombia rifles, pistols,
machine guns, rockets, grenades and even bulletproof vests for
Colombian officials and judges who prosecute drug traffickers.
   The four-engine C-130s can take off and land on 3,000-foot
runways, even dirt airstrips, and could be used in raids on remote
coca-leaf plantations and refining laboratories.
   The government gave no reason for removing police Col. Antonio
Sanchez as chief of a special 4,000-member anti-drug unit in
Medellin. A source at national police headquarters in Bogota,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said he was ousted for dealing
with drug traffickers.
   But in a telephone interview with the Associated Press, Sanchez
said the report that he had been relieved of command for alleged
links to drug traffickers was ``absolutely false.''
   The chief of national police, Gen. Miguel Gomez Padilla, said
Sanchez was under no suspicion or investigation and was merely being
transferred to headquarters in Bogota.
   Barco, who has vowed not to back down from the cocaine bosses,
also on Sunday took a helicopter flight over the wreckage of the
Bogota newspaper El Espectador, which on Saturday was bombed by
drug-cartel terrorists.
   Eighty-four people were injured in the blast. The paper printed a
smaller edition from a makeshift newsroom.
   ``We will continue moving forward!'' the front page proclaimed.
``In its 102 years, El Espectador has always gone ahead, overcoming
all adversities,'' said the paper, whose publisher was assassinated
in 1986 by drug traffickers.
   The drug cartels, which last month assassinated Colombia's
leading presidential candidate and also the top police official in
the cocaine center of Medellin, have declared ``total and absolute
war'' against the government.
</TEXT>
