<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 0100EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Poll-Labor Bjt   09-04 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll-Labor, Bjt,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Strong Support for Raising Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans overwhelmingly favor an increase in the
federal minimum wage, even though most workers are generally
satisfied with their pay, a national poll has found.
   Nearly nine in 10 respondents to the Media General-Associated
Press poll wanted the hourly miniumum raised from $3.35, and
two-thirds of them favored the $4.55 minimum approved by Congress
but vetoed by President Bush in June.
   At the same time, six in 10 supported Bush's proposal for a
``training wage'' under which new workers could be kept at $3.35 for
their first six months on the job. Congress has not adopted that
plan.
   On other workplace issues this Labor Day, nearly four in 10
respondents said they would join a labor union at their workplace,
even though most regarded management more favorably than they viewed
unions.
   Most workers gave favorable ratings to their salaries, job
conditions and time off, the survey found. But pensions were a sore
point, and more than a third were unhappy with their pay.
   In a Gallup Poll, meanwhile, most full-time American workers said
they were satisfied with their jobs. Twenty-eight percent said they
were completely satisfied with their job and 60 percent said they
were mostly satisfied, while 3 percent said they were completely
dissatisfied.
   Many of the 1,163 adult respondents to the Media
General-Associated Press poll saw unions as weakening, and few
objected to that trend. Still, 49 percent said workers are better
off with a union, while 31 percent disagreed.
   Overall, 47 percent said they were unwilling to join a union,
while 37 percent said they would join one. Seven in 10 favored
so-called right-to-work laws, which ban mandatory union membership.
And while 44 percent had a favorable opinion of unions, 64 percent
thought favorably of management.
   Rating their own circumstances at work, respondents gave top
grades to the safety of their workplace _ 87 percent said excellent
or good _ and overall working conditions, with 81 percent favorable.
   Nearly seven in 10 were happy with their time off, 61 percent
rated their health benefits favorably and 60 percent said their
salary was excellent or good, as opposed to fair or poor.
   Pension benefits received the lowest ratings. Of those with an
opinion, just 46 percent viewed their pension plans favorably, while
41 percent were dissatisfied. A quarter called their pension
benefits poor.
   But benefits were not the prime concern: Fifty-four percent said
they would prefer better wages to better benefits. Just 15 percent
said their salaries were excellent.
   White-collar, management employees were less concerned with
wages: Seven in 10 rated their salaries favorably, compared with 57
percent of blue-collar workers and of non-management white collar
workers.
   While 83 percent of union members said that workers are better
off with unions, 46 percent of management employees said that
workers are better off non-unionized.
   Southerners also were more dubious of unions _ they divided about
evenly on the question. More than half of the respondents ages 18-29
and those over 64 said workers are better off with unions.
   Union membership, declining over the years, now accounts for just
under 17 percent of the workforce.
   Among respondents who are not union workers now, 38 percent in
the youngest group ruled out joining a union. That rose to about 50
percent of the older groups.
   Forty-three percent overall said unions are getting weaker and
just 15 percent said they are getting stronger. Still, 33 percent
said unions are too strong, while 20 percent said they are too weak.
   The poll was conducted by telephone in July. It had a margin of
error of plus or minus 3 points for all respondents and 4 points for
the 812 who were employed full time or part time.
   The Gallup Poll also was conducted in July. It questioned 697
adults employed full time and had a 4-point margin of error.
   Media General Inc., a communications company based in Richmond,
Va., publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News
Leader, the Tampa (Fla.) Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.)
Journal, and operates TV stations WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in Charleston,
S.C., and WJKS in Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890904-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 0102EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Poll-Method     09-04 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll-Method,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll on Labor Reached 1,163 Nationwide</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poll-Labor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is based
on telephone interviews July 7-16 with 1,163 adults in the
continental United States. Phone numbers were selected randomly and
interviews were conducted with the adult who had the most recent
birthday, a random phenomenon.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the sample.
The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning that 19 of 20 times
its findings should be within 3 points of the result if every adult
American were asked the same questions. The error margin is larger
for subgroups _ 4 points for respondents who held jobs, for example,
and 6 points for those age 18-29.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions in this
poll; because of rounding, sums may not total 100:
   1. The minimum wage has been $3.35 per hour since January 1981.
Do you think it should be increased, or not? Yes: 87 percent. No: 10
percent. Don't know or no answer: 3 percent.
   2. (If yes) One plan would raise the minimum wage to $4.55 per
hour over a three-year period. Another plan would raise it to $4.25
over three years. Which do you prefer _ a $4.55 minimum wage or a
$4.25 minimum wage. $4.55: 64. $4.25: 33. DK-NA: 3.
   3. (If yes to No. 1) One plan would include a training wage _
meaning that new workers could be kept at the current $3.35 minimum
wage for their first six months on the job. Do you support or oppose
that training wage proposal? Support: 60. Oppose: 36. DK-NA: 4.
   4. Are you employed either full time or part time? Full: 60.
Part: 10. Not employed: 30.
   5. (If employed) Is the job you hold considered a blue-collar
job, or not? Yes: 38. No: 60. DK-NA: 2.
   6. (If no) Is the job you hold considered a management job, or
not? Yes: 49. No: 50. DK-NA: 2.
   7a. Would you rate your overall working conditions as excellent,
good, only fair or poor? Excellent: 35. Good: 46. Fair: 15. Poor: 3.
DK-NA: 1.
   b. ... the safety of your workplace? Excellent: 41. Good: 46.
Fair: 10. Poor: 3. DK-NA: 1
   c. ... your health benefits? Excellent: 27. Good: 34. Fair: 15.
Poor: 15. DK-NA: 8.
   d. ... your pension benefits? Excellent: 20. Good: 26. Fair: 16.
Poor: 25. DK-NA: 14.
