<FIRST>r w PM-PandaDies Bjt   09-04 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panda Dies, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tiny Cub Dies After 39-Hour Fight Against Infection</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WX6, WX7</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Zoo officials are turning their hopes
for a successful panda cub birth to next year, following the death
of female panda Ling-Ling's fifth cub from an infection.
   The unnamed male cub died Sunday after 39 hours of fighting the
infection transmitted from its mother, zoo officials said.
   Although Ling-Ling is 20 years old _ the oldest panda surviving
in any zoo _ there have been cases in China where pandas older
Ling-Ling have given birth, said zoo director Michael Robinson.
   ``Behaviorally, Ling-Ling has shown every indication of being an
excellent mother,'' Robinson said.
   ``We're not doing this out of any whim or whimsy ... We're doing
it to save a species,'' Robinson said.
   ``We'll face next year with more knowledge and experience than
ever before,'' said Lisa Stevens, manager in charge of the zoo's
Panda House.
   As her human handlers recounted Ling-Ling's latest travails at a
news conference Sunday, the black-and-white animal sat in her nest
cradling apples put there in place of her missing baby.
   The tiny cub, weighing only 3.1 ounces, was born prematurely
Friday at the National Zoo and taken from its 250-pound mother six
hours later because of concern of infection.
   Zoo officials said the cub first began showing signs of strength,
but then weakened despite around-the-clock efforts by zoo
veterinarians and pediatric experts enlisted from nearby Children's
Hospital.
   The cub was placed in an incubator, fed a special formula through
a tube into its stomach and given antibiotics to fight the
infection, officials said.
   ``Every effort was made to pull this cub through its illness,''
said Robinson. At one point, when zoo officials managed to separate
the cub from a sedated mother, he recalled, ``I thought we'd won.''
   Without human aid, ``the baby would have died well before it did.
The infection would have run away with it,'' he said.
   Mitchell Bush, chief veterinarian at the zoo, said the cub's
survival was an uphill struggle because of the premature birth and
the infection. During most of its 39 hours of life the care given
the cub was similar to what a prematurely born child would receive.
   Zoo officials said a small tube inserted down the cub's throat
and into its stomach was ``slightly mispositioned'' and that a
``minute'' amount of fluid entered the cub's lung cavity. But Bush
said the amount of fluid was so small that it did not contribute to
the cub's death.
   Bush said there had been concern from the start that the cub
might have caught an infection from its mother, which has had
problems periodically with a kidney infection since 1983 and had a
reoccurrence only a week ago. The tiny cub's chances of survival
were reduced further because it weighed only about three-fourths of
what a normal panda cub would weigh, officials said.
   Three of the four previous cubs born to Ling-Ling also died of
infection shortly after birth, with the longest-living cub surviving
for four days in 1987. Because of the mother's problems with
infection, a decision was made nearly two years ago to take any
future newborn away from the mother, Bush said. That approach had
never been tried before, officials acknowledged.
   No giant panda cub has yet been successfully bred in captivity in
the United States, although cubs have survived at zoos in Mexico,
Japan, Spain and China, the native home for giant pandas.
   ``The zoo staff will do whatever is humanly possible to provide
the necessary care to support any future pregnancies and births,''
Robinson said.
   Ms. Stevens said Ling-Ling returned to the Panda House after the
anesthesia wore off and began searching for her offspring. Zoo
keepers found after previous births that if apples are put into the
nest, the mother will for a time mistake them for the cub.
   ``She still has her apples and is sitting in her nest cradling
them,'' said Ms. Stevens. The father, Hsing-Hsing, was in a separate
pen.
   Ling-Ling and Hsing-Hsing, which were given to the United States
by the Chinese government in 1972, are the only giant pandas on
permanent display in the country. Pandas are an endangered species
with fewer than 1,000 counted worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
