<FIRST>r w PM-China-EscapedOfficial     09-04 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Escaped Official,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former High-Ranking Chinese Official Emerges From Hiding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The highest-ranking Chinese official known to
have escaped from that country since the violent repression of
pro-democracy demonstrators is calling for an international effort
to bring down officials who ordered the massacre, The Washington
Post reported today.
   Chen Yizi, a former leader of China's economic reform movement,
emerged from hiding in Paris three months after leaving China, the
Post said.
   He criticized the Bush administration's response to the killings
in Tiananmen Square on June 3-4, the Post said.
   The crackdown was provoked by hard-liners in the Chinese
government in an effort to gain control over the communist regime
and put an end to Zhao Ziyang's economic reform movement, Chen was
quoted as saying.
   Chen said he is organizing the Front for a Democratic China, to
be headquartered in Paris, adding that it will seek support from
Chinese exiles and other Chinese who live overseas.
   The Post said Chen would have liked to have the organization
headquartered in the United States.
   ``But the United States government has appeared to be reluctant
to grant visas to dissidents and to help us be effective
politically, while France has been very helpful,'' he was quoted as
saying. ``The attitude of the Bush administration has been
disappointing when you compare it to the support and sympathy we
receive from Congress.''
   The Bush administration imposed limited sanctions on China
following the crackdown. Chen said that if those sanctions are
weakened, ``that is oxygen for Li Peng's government, and a bad
investment for America because Li Peng's government cannot last
long.''
   Chen was the head of China's Institute for Economic Structural
Reform that helped Zhao carry out many of that country's economic
reforms.
   Chen, 49, said he was aware in May that he was being followed in
China, and he told the Post he left Beijing on June 5, two days
after the military action began in Tiananmen Square. He gave no
details of how he escaped China.
   Chen described to the Post a May 17 meeting of the Chinese
Politburo in which Zhao resigned under pressure from hard-liners who
wanted to crack down on the student demonstrators.
   The student demonstrations brought to a head a two-year-old power
struggle in the Politburo over the reform issue, Chen told the Post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
