<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-04 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ousted Gay Congressman Sees `Deja Vu' in Barney Frank Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gay former congressman who was forced out of
office by a sex scandal nine years ago says the uproar over Rep.
Barney Frank's relationship with a male prostitute sounds all too
familiar.
   ``It has the strange familiarity of what Yogi Berra might have
called `deja vu all over again','' former Rep. Robert Bauman, a
Republican, wrote Sunday in an article in The Washington Post on the
controversy involving Frank, a Democrat.
   Frank last month confirmed published reports that he had
solicited and then befriended a male prostitute, allowed him to use
his Washington apartment, and paid him $20,000 a year from private
funds to do various chores. Frank acknowledged being gay in 1987.
   The prostitute, Steven Gobie, claimed he operated a prostitution
service out of Frank's apartment and that the Massachusetts
congressman knew about it. Frank has denied any such knowledge and
has received signs of continuing strong support in his home district.
   Bauman called Gobie a ``louse'' and a ``despicable character,''
and warned the media and Congress against censuring Frank because of
private acts, saying, ``the end result will be the decimation of
government.''
   Bauman was defeated in his Maryland district after eight years in
Congress in 1980 when it was revealed he was gay and had been
arrested for soliciting a male prostitute.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S.-Soviet Negotiators To Discuss North Pacific Fishing Issues</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet negotiators meet in Leningrad
later this month to talk about the illegal harvesting of salmon in
the North Pacific and possible regulation of bottom fishing off
Alaska.
   The agenda may also include a discussion of the use of drift nets
in the North Pacific, said Ed Wolfe, the State Department's
ambassador for oceans and fisheries. He said an international ban or
regulation of such fishing may be ``possible'' after additional
scientific information is collected.
   The U.S. delegation will include 10 advisers from the fishing
industry in Alaska and Washington state.
   Both the United States and the Soviet Union are interested in
negotiating a new salmon agreement that ``would be comprehensive and
could potentially replace'' the International North Pacific
Fisheries Convention (INPFC), said Wolfe.
   `The existing convention has been very effective since it was
signed in the 1950s, but times have changed, the players have
changed and there is a need for more regulation and cooperation that
goes beyond the INPFC mandate,'' said Wolfe. ``In addition, the
Soviets are not members of the INPFC.''
   The United States, Japan and Canada are the current members.
   Wolfe said the Soviets have made a tentative proposal and the
United States would offer a counterproposal during the Leningrad
talks.
   U.S. fishing groups have long insisted that foreign fishermen
have been illegally catching salmon on the high seas, and say such
activity has hurt salmon runs in Alaska, Washington state and Oregon.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen police officers were killed during
drug enforcement activities across the United States in 1988, says
the Washington-based Crime Control Institute.
   Such killings of police officers have averaged seven a year since
1972, when the FBI began publishing narratives on how police
officers died in the line of duty, according to a report released by
the institute on Sunday.
   University of Maryland Professor Lawrence W. Sherman, who also
heads the institute, said part of the reason for the increase is
that drug enforcement activity is increasing.
   Estimated drug arrests have set a record each year since reaching
708,000 in 1984, rising to 1.1 million in 1988, Sherman said.
   The numbers of police murders per 100,000 drug arrests rose from
.71 to in 1984 to 1.22 per 100,000 in 1988.
   The record rate, however, was in 1976, when 1.96 officers died
per 100,000 arrests, followed by 1980 when there were 1.89 police
killings for every 100,000 drug arrests.
   ``While the risk of death per arrest is still not as high as in
the record years of 1976 and 1980, this trend is still an ominous
one,'' the study said.
</TEXT>
