<HEAD>Reports: Bloomingdale's to Open Moscow Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bloomingdale's, symbol of conspicuous
consumption, may be heading to Moscow. But the average Soviet
citizen probably won't get a chance to line up for its perfume or
jeans.
   The department store chain's Soviet branches are expected to
accept only Western currencies, while Ivan Q. Public has only rubles
to spend. Rubles legally cannot be converted into other currencies.
   The retailer has had serious discussions with Soviet officials
about opening two shops by next spring _ at a Moscow hotel and
airport, said Bloomingdale's chairman, Marvin S. Traub.
   He said they would be like the ``Bloomie's Express'' shops, where
merchandise with the Bloomingdale label is sold.
   In May, Bloomingdale's began capitalizing on ``Gorbymania'' by
selling Soviet goods at its Upper East Side store, which was the
scene of a defection in the movie ``Moscow on the Hudson.''
   The newspaper Moscow Pravda said Bloomingdale's and the Moscow
City Council signed a letter of intent for the joint venture.
