<FIRST>r a PM-ArsonApology     09-04 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arson Apology,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Whites Appear in Black Church to Apologize for Arson Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADAIRVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a church founded by freed
slaves gave a resounding ``Amen!'' to four whites who came to say
they were sorry for setting their building on fire.
   The four pleaded guilty in October to breaking into church in
southern Kentucky and setting it on fire in May 1986.
   Before their sentencing, they had paid $6,000 to rebuild the
116-year-old church, and prosecutors agreed to amend the charges
from felonies to misdemeanors.
   In sentencing them, Logan District Judge Dale L. Prince ordered
them to apologize to the congregation or face contempt of court,
with a possible year in jail and $500 fine.
   ``I think the general consensus of all of us here is that we are
just amazed that this type of thing could happen,'' said 56-year-old
Sarah Garrick, who grew up next to the church and now lives in
Chicago.
   ``When I lived here, this would have never have happened because
of the racial prejudices in the area. I think it's wonderful that
the court made them come out here and apologize.''
   On Saturday, Bill Sircy, 22, bowed his head and cleared his
throat during the dedication of the new Smith Grove AME Zion Church
before saying, ``We're sorry, but I know that's not enough.''
   Angela B. Estep, about 19, added: ``What we did was wrong. ... It
was an accident, but it was still wrong. And I'm sorry.''
   The others who offered apologies were Sherri Davenport, 19, and
Danny Smith, 22.
   The Rev. Erskine Wade tried to ease their fears before they spoke
to 60 members of the congregation.
   ``Don't be nervous; you're among friends,'' Wade told them. ``And
when I say friends, I mean friends. What happened, happened. And
there is nothing any of us can do about that. We are your friends
now, and we want to help you any way we can.''
   Wade said that because the four made restitution, most church
members were not hostile toward them.
   ``Most are trying to be Christians, and I think they have
sympathy for them. There's no animosity, just sympathy.''
</TEXT>
