<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-04 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose to a two-month high against the
Japanese yen today in spite of intervention by the central bank,
while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange climbed for the first
time in four days.
   The dollar closed at 146.13 yen, up 0.68 yen from Friday's close
of 145.45 yen. It started trading at 145.90 yen and moved in a range
of 145.85-146.30 yen.
   It was the first time since June 15 for the currency to rise
above the 126-yen mark.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's advance followed U.S.
government reports released Friday showing the country's continued
economic growth.
   ``Last week's labor statistics reconfirmed the strength of the
U.S. economy, encouraging the purchase of the dollar,'' said a
dealer at Daiichi Kangyo Bank, speaking anonymously.
   The U.S. Labor Department reported the nation's unemployment rate
for August remained steady at 5.2 percent, unchanged from the
previous month, while the Commerce Department said the Index of
Leading Economic Indicators, the chief economic forecasting gauge,
rose in July for the first time in three months.
   ``The dollar's bullish sentiment remains firm'' in Tokyo, though
the New York market will be closed Monday for the Labor Day holiday,
said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, also speaking anonymously.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which has been bearish since Tuesday, won back 135.56
points, or 0.38 percent, to close at 34,483.78.
   Securities dealers said the dollar's rise discouraged investors
from actively buying shares, but ``the market environment is
gradually improving.''
   ``There was some active selling of export-related shares,
triggered by the dollar's strength, but by the day's end, most of
them were bought back, primarily by institutional investors,'' said
a dealer at Nikko Securities Co., speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
