<HEAD>Air Raid On Palestinian Guerrilla Bases In Southeast Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with 4 guerrillas wounded. Picks
up 4th graf `Majdal Balhis ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RASHAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes blasted a Palestinian
guerrilla base in a rare pre-dawn air raid in southeast Lebanon
today, wounding at least four guerrillas, police said.
   The Israeli army confirmed the 2 a.m. attack on the village of
Majdal Balhis in the foothills of Mount Hermon. An army spokesman
said a guerrilla base was destroyed and all raiding planes returned
safely to base.
   Lebanese police said at least four guerrillas were wounded in the
attack on the village, which is 6 miles north of Israel's
self-designated ``security zone'' in south Lebanon.
   Majdal Balhis houses a major base for Ahmed Jibril's Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, said the PFLP-GC base was ``totally destroyed'' in the
raid, which followed two attacks Wednesday and Thursday in which
Katyusha rockets were fired at Israel's Galilee district from south
Lebanon.
   Those attacks caused no injuries, but one rocket damaged a house
in Kiryat Shmona in the Galilee Panhandle.
   The Katyusha attacks were blamed on Hezbollah, or Party of God, a
pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem fundamentalist Lebanese faction.
   Israeli troops fought a battle with four guerrillas just north of
the border on Thursday, and one militiamen of the Shiite group Amal
was killed. Israel suffered no casualties in the firefight.
   It was not clear why the Israeli air force struck at Palestinian
guerrillas instead of the Lebanese factions who that have been
blamed for the recent hostilities against Israel.
   The PFLP-GC is a radical guerrilla faction at odds with Yasser
Arafat's maisntream Palestine Liberation Organization. It is based
in Damascus and funded mainly by Libya.
   Today's air strike was Israel's second in Lebanon in nine days
and the 11th this year. By police count, 17 people were killed and
94 wounded in the 10 previous air raids since Jan. 11.
</TEXT>
