<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--AirCollision     09-04 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Air Collision,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helicopter, Small Plane Collide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUMA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter collided with a small plane,
killing three people and scattering debris over a rural subdivision,
authorities said.
   Two people in the helicopter and the pilot of the single-engine
plane were killed in SUnday night's crash about a mile from the
Houma-Terrebonne Airport, said police Capt. John Dixon.
   Dixon said the helicopter crashed and burned in an intersection
just outside Houma's southern limits and the plane crashed into a
tree, but there were no injuries on the ground.
   The helicopter was leased by Acadian Ambulance Service from
Petroleum Helicopters Inc., which serves the offshore oil industry.
The crew had just flown from the hospital for maintenance work on
their regular helicopter and were returning in a backup aircraft
when the collision occurred, said Acadian Ambulance spokesman
Richard Zuschlag.
   ``There is no explanation for it. It was a mid-air collision.
Nobody knows who was at fault,'' Zuschlag said.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators were expected
to investigate the crash today, he said.
