<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--WichitaEagle     09-04 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Wichita Eagle,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Drops `Beacon' From Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Wichita Eagle-Beacon is now The Wichita
Eagle, laying to rest a newspaper name that survived nearly 117
years.
   With the Sunday editions, the newspaper dropped the word Beacon
from its name. Its publishing company retains its corporate name,
The Wichita Eagle and Beacon Publishing Co. Inc.
   ``We're not changing the name. We're shortening the name,'' said
Executive Editor Davis ``Buzz'' Merritt Jr. ``If we were changing it
to `The Gazette,' or something, I think that would cause a stir. And
it should. We're just dropping the name of a newspaper that hasn't
existed for nine years.''
   The Wichita Beacon, which like the Eagle was founded in 1872, was
last published as a separate afternoon newspaper in October 1980.
   Reid Ashe, publisher of the Knight-Ridder Inc.-owned newspaper,
said a question about possibly changing the name was included in a
recent reader poll.
   ``Almost no one said they cared. So we think it's a safe and
sensible change,'' he said.
</TEXT>
