<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     09-04 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunbattles Across Green Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian troops clashed in
gunbattles across Beirut's dividing Green Line today after
night-long artillery duels that kindled forest fires in the central
mountains.
   Police reported no casualties in the morning hostilities along
the three-mile demarcation line that splits Beirut into Moslem and
Christian sectors.
   At least 826 people have been killed and 2,449 wounded in
fighting that broke out March 8 between Gen. Michel Aoun's Christian
army units and Syrian troops.
   Police said troops of the Syria's elite Special Forces fired
machine guns and hurled grenades on the Lebanese Army's 9th brigade
at Beirut's bomb-ravaged port on the western tip of the Green Line.
   The Lebanese soldiers retaliated with tank fire and truck-mounted
machine guns, said a police spokesman who cannot be named in line
with standing rules.
   The clashes later spread to the southern slums, where the
Syrians, barricaded in Beirut's shuttered airport, exchanged
artillery and tank fire with Aoun's 10th brigade soldiers on nearby
hills, the spokesman added.
   Artillery duels had flared from dusk Sunday to dawn in the
mountain resort towns of Douar, Btigrin, Ein el-Tuffaha and Bekfaya,
starting fires in the pine stands that burned all night.
   The towns form the eastern entrance into the Christian enclave
north of Beirut that has been besieged by the Syrians and their
Moslem allies since mid-March.
   Syria's main ally, Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt, said in a
statement published by several Beirut newspapers today that Aoun
should leave Lebanon as a precondition for a settlement with the
Christians.
   ``Aoun has pleaded for French help, but France did not come to
his rescue. He also sought America's help and the United States did
not respond.
   ``What is Aoun waiting for? Let him leave. I am willing to take
him out of Lebanon. He should go in order to avert further bloodshed
and destruction,'' Jumblatt said.
   He vowed to fight on to the bitter end if Aoun stays and said:
``Mr. General, please spare us further death and misery. Please go.
Go wherever you want, but out of Lebanon.''
   Aoun's spokesmen at the bomb-battered presidential palace in
suburban Baabda declined to comment on Jumblatt's statement.
   The confrontation erupted when Aoun ordered his gunboats and
helicopter gunships on March 6 to blockade three militia-run harbors
south of Beirut, two of them run by Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist
Party.
   Jumblatt retaliated by shelling the Christian enclave. The
Syrians later jointed the bombardment and sealed off the enclave to
prevent Aoun from receiving arms from Iraq, his main Arab backer and
Syria's arch rival.
   The Syrians intervened in 1976 under a peacekeeping mandate from
the Arab League. But Aoun maintains that Syria's credibility was
eroded when its troops sided with Moslems in the 14-year-old
Lebanese civil war.
</TEXT>
