<FIRST>r a PM-DeadlyCrash     09-04 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deadly Crash,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Town Mourns Death of Six Teens in One-Car Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WRIGHTSTOWN, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This shocked town of 1,000 began
mourning the deaths of six high school students in a weekend car
crash that went undiscovered for 18 to 20 hours.
   At St. Paul Roman Catholic Church, parishioners listened only to
gentle, reassuring organ music at Sunday Mass, the Rev. Richard
Shafer said, because, ```I didn't think they were in the mood to
sing.''
   ``In a school of 300 high school kids everybody knows them,''
Principal Jack Lewis said. He said school would resume Tuesday with
a team of counselors standing by.
   The five boys and a girl were killed when their borrowed car
veered from a gravel road and plunged down an embankment into a
shallow creek, Brown County Sheriff Leon Pieschek said in Green Bay.
   The accident site in the town of Holland, neighboring Wrightstown
in northeastern Wisconsin, was strewn with more than a dozen beer
bottles, and the 17-year-old driver is believed to have attended a
beer party before the crash, Pieschek said. Autopsies and
blood-alcohol tests were being conducted, he said.
   He said the accident probably occurred between 10 p.m. and
midnight Friday but was not discovered until 6 p.m. Saturday.
   The victims were Jamie Borchardt, 17, the driver; Stacie Summers,
15; Chad Bungeon, 15; Eugene Carter, 17, and his younger brothers,
Sean, 16, and Corey, 14. Lewis called them ``typical teen-age kids
for this area.''
   The sheriff said three people were arrested Friday night at a
beer party on private property in Greenleaf, a few miles east of
Holland, and it is believed at least one of the victims, Borchardt,
attended.
   Officers raided the party about midnight after receiving
complaints that people were throwing beer bottles and rocks at
passing cars, but none of the victims were at the party then,
Pieschek said.
   Some teen-agers who gathered outside the church after Mass said
they knew the victims from school and heard they had been at the
party.
   ``They all took off before it got raided,'' 14-year-old Melanie
Buechler said.
   The sheriff said one of the victims' families filed a missing
child report Saturday while the other victims' families conducted
their own searches without reporting to his department.
   The crash was discovered by a 14-year-old walking near the creek.
</TEXT>
