<HEAD>Thunderstorms Strike Nebraska</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms developing ahead of a cold front rumbled
over Nebraska early today, producing torrential downpours, damaging
winds and large hail.
   Five inches of rain fell from a thunderstorm today at Fremont and
more than 3 inches of rain drenched Blair. Nearly 2} inches of rain
fell in a half-hour at Oconto.
   Winds gusted to 72 mph near Columbus, Neb., and brought down tree
limbs and power lines at Schuyler. Golf ball-size hail fell at
Keystone, Springview and Schuyler, and marble-size hail piled up to
6 inches deep in parts of Cherry and Sheridan counties.
   The same cold front also triggered intense thunderstorms over
eastern South Dakota. Golf ball-size hail fell south of Clear Lake,
and winds gusted to 70 mph at Castlewood.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms developed over northwest Oklahoma, with
dime-size hail falling at Oakwood. Thunderstorms also struck the
northern Florida Peninsula, and showers and thunderstorms dampened
New Mexico.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included nearly 2\ inches at Sioux City, Iowa, nearly 2 inches at
Norfolk, Neb., and 1} inches at Jacksonville, Fla.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms over the
eastern Gulf Coast, the Florida Peninsula, Georgia, South Carolina,
the western Great Lakes, the upper and middle Mississippi Valley,
Kansas and Oklahoma.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s over eastern New England and
along parts of the Atlantic Coast; in the 90s in Florida, the lower
Mississippi Valley, the southern Plains, southern New Mexico and
central Texas; in the 100s in the desert Southwest and interior
valleys of California; and in the 70s and 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 31
degrees at Houlton, Maine, to 89 degrees at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Albany, N.Y. 50 fair; Atlanta 73 windy; Boston 57 fair;
