<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     09-04 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Begins in Soviet Azerbaijan in Reply to People's Front Call</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some bus drivers and factory workers stayed off the
job today in Soviet Azerbaijan on the first day of a strike called
by a grassroots political group to put pressure on the Communist
leadership, officials said.
   Representatives of Azerbaijan's Foreign Ministry, the official
Azerinform news agency and an independent journalist said at midday
that it was too early to say how effective the strike call had been,
but it did not appear to have a crippling effect on the local
economy.
   At a rally in the southern republic's capital of Baku attended by
hundreds of thousands of people, supporters of the Azerbaijan
People's Front on Saturday declared a weeklong general strike
beginning today to press its demands.
   The People's Front wants new elections to replace the republic's
representation in the Soviet Congress and the abolition of direct
rule by the Kremlin in the Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan,
which is predominantly Armenian.
   Izmail Agayev, head of the Information Department of Azerbaijan's
Foreign Ministry, said by telephone from Baku today that some
drivers of buses and streetcars in the city of 1.7 million did not
show up for work.
   ``Some of the factory workers are also on strike,'' said Agayev.
   An editor at Azerinform said the strike idled some enterprises in
the major oil refining and processing center on the Caspian Sea
coast. At others, he said, about 70 percent of the workers were on
the job.
   Alif Aliev, an independent Baku journalist, said it was too early
to gauge the effectiveness of the strike call from the People's
Front.
   The Defense Ministry newspaper Red Star said Sunday that tensions
between Armenia and neighboring Azerbaijan ``are like gunpowder,''
and that Nagorno-Karabakh is on the verge of civil war.
   The disputed region is wracked by strikes and frequent armed
clashes. Most of its roads are closed, and Red Star described how
locals fired on Soviet troops recently and an angry crowd surrounded
a police station to demand the releast of detainees.
   Tens of thousands of people in Nagorno-Karabakh have been forced
to flee their homes because of clashes between Armenians and
Azerbaijanis that have killed more than 100 people.
   In an effort to halt the violence, Moscow on Jan. 12 imposed
direct rule on Azerbaijan by a committee led by its special
representative, Arkady Volsky.
   Azerbaijani People's Front leaders including Ekhitbar Mamedov,
poet Bakhtiar Vakhabzade and chairman Abulfaz Aliev termed direct
Kremlin rule over Nagorno-Karabakh ``a gross violation of the
people's right to self-determination,'' Amirbekov said.
   A council of Armenian activists in Nagorno-Karabakh declared
their independence from Azerbaijan last week, but the Azerbaijan
government rejected the move as unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
