<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Barry Hyams</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Broadway producer and theater
publicist Barry Hyams died Friday after suffering a heart attack at
his home. He was 78.
   Hyams, a native of New York, produced ``Ulysses in Nighttown''
with Zero Mostel, ``Clerembard'' and ``Endgame,'' among other works.
   Hyams also did the publicity for ``Kismet,'' ``A Man for All
Seasons,'' ``Medea'' with Judith Anderson and ``Bus Stop'' with Kim
Stanley.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Richard Sandler</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Sandler, an assistant managing editor and
sports editor at Newsday, died Sunday of cancer. He was 50.
   Sandler worked in the news departments of The Sun in Baltimore
and The Philadelphia Inquirer before coming to Newsday, a daily
newspaper on Long Island, as a news editor. In 1973, he became
sports editor.
   Sandler was a graduate of Rutgers University and the Columbia
School of Journalism. He also served in the Marine Corps.
   A resident of Northport, N.Y., Sandler is survived by his mother,
Etta, of Wynnewood, Pa.; sister Toby Lorry of Huntingdon Valley,
Pa.; wife, Gloria, sons Steven and Peter, and daughter Brynn.
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
