<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     09-04 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Try to Control Killings of Suspected Collaborators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underground Palestinian leaders today told
residents of the Israeli-occupied territories to stop killing
suspected collaborators without approval from the leadership.
   The statement appeared to be aimed at stemming a rash of killings
that have left 106 Arabs dead since the Palestinian uprising began
in December 1987. Most of the dead were accused of collaborating,
but some were suspected of drug sales or prostitution.
   Nearly two-thirds of the deaths have occurred this year,
including 13 in August and six this month.
   The Israeli army says at least 245 collaborators have also been
wounded by fellow Arabs.
   In their latest underground leaflet, leaders of the revolt said
Palestinians ``should refrain from rash decisions'' about suspected
collaborators and consult the uprising leaders before warning or
punishing them.
   ``A chance should be given to repent, and dialogue and
watchfulness should be employed as a better alternative than
punishment,'' said the leaflet, which was circulated in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Israeli officials on Sunday announced that rules for shooting at
suspected enforcers of the uprising would be broadened. They said
Israeli forces would be allowed to use live ammunition at any hour
of the day or night to stop masked Palestinians trying to avoid
arrest.
   Sources said that previously troops could only use live
ammunition in such circumstances at night.
   There have been increasing reports that Israeli security forces
are arming collaborators. The Hebrew daily Maariv said today that
the Arabs were also receiving weapons training.
   In scattered clashes today in the territories, seven Palestinians
were reported wounded by army gunfire.
   In the 21-month uprising aimed at ending Israeli rule, 557
Palestinians have been killed by Israeli soldiers or civilians, and
39 Israelis have died in the violence.
   Also today, two members of the Civil Guard were dismissed for
failing to act on reports that subordinates beat 20 Arabs three
weeks ago in a dormitory. Five of the Arabs were hospitalized.
   The independent Yediot Ahronot said that in addition to beating
the Arabs, the volunteer policemen took them to a rooftop and
insisted they hit each other.
</TEXT>
