<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 1155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-AlaskaQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0519 09-04 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alaska Quake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0519,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Hits Off Alaska; Seismic Sea Wave Fails to Materialize</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with warning lifted. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMER, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful earthquake off Alaska early
today prompted 5,000 residents of Kodiak to take to higher ground
for fear a seismic sea wave would hit at dawn, but the threat
subsided without incident, officials said.
   The quake registering 6.9 on Richter scale struck at 9:15 a.m.
EDT and was centered about 140 miles southwest of Kodiak Island,
said the U.S. Geological Survey in Golden, Colo. There was no
immediate indication the quake was felt on land.
   George Carte, a seismologist at the Alaska Tsunami Warning
Center, had warned of a possible tsunami in Alaska and British
Columbia, with Kodiak the first point to be hit about 11 a.m. EDT,
but lifted the warning within hours.
   ``We're past our ETA and there's been no wave action,'' said
Kodiak police dispatcher Kathy Cliver. Police said they would allow
some 5,000 residents back into their homes in the island community
at the foot of a mountain.
   Carte said the center's gauge at Sand Point, 180 miles west of
the quake's epicenter, recorded a small tsunami of less than
one-half foot.
   ``Therefore, no destructive tsunami threat exists for coastal
areas in the Pacific,'' he said.
   ``Some small sea-level changes may be recorded, however, as local
conditions can cause a wide variation in tsunami wave action. The
all-clear determinations must be made by local authorities.''
   Carte gave no estimate of how big a wave generated by the quake
might be.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion in which every
increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 7 is a major quake, capable of widespread heavy
damage.
   The 1964 Alaska quake that killed 131 people measured 8.4, while
the San Francisco quake of 1906 was estimated to register 8.3.
</TEXT>
