<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 1212EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HighwayKillings     09-04 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highway Killings Probe: Costs Spiral While Fresh Leads Subside</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is it someone you see at church? Is it a sailor who
passed through town? It could be either or one of thousands of
others, say experts working on a serial murder case that's raised
many questions and yielded few answers.
   For a while Ronald Ray Griffith looked like a solid suspect.
   He drifted into southeastern Massachusetts about the time the
first of nine victims was reported missing and took off again last
fall, just as the bodies stopped turning up along highways.
   But when officials finally arranged to have Griffiths brought to
the seaport of New Bedford from Missouri, where he's serving time
for larceny, the unemployed carpenter's ``tips'' didn't pan out.
   Griffiths toyed with investigators before a lie detector test
confirmed he didn't know anything about the crimes, said Jim Martin,
spokesman for District Attorney Ronald A. Pina.
   And so it has gone in the 10 months local, state and federal
authorities have tracked the deaths of nine women and disappearances
of two others, all of them linked with Weld Square, a district known
for drugs and prostitution.
   The probe has cost $109,000 and 3,930 overtime hours.
   Undercover investigators have spent months on New Bedford's
seedier streets, questioning prostitutes and drug dealers who are
often fogged by alcohol, cocaine or heroin, Martin said.
   ``The circumstances surrounding the New Beford slayings are the
circumstances of sleaze and that's one of the critical problems,''
he said.
   Martin said the list of suspects was narrowed from four to three
once Griffiths was discounted and the probe's end is nowhere in
sight.
   ``We are by no means at a point where there's been any
consideration of pulling back,'' Martin said. ``There's a lot of
work to be done.''
   But serial murder experts say the money may never produce the
answers the victims' relatives crave and investigators seek.
   ``The odds are growing slimmer daily,'' said Jack Levin, a
criminal justice professor at Northeastern University and co-author
of ``Mass Murder: America's Growing Menace.''
   Some experts say investigators should look close to home; others
insist the assailants move on. They disagree on whether systematic
murderers inevitably lash out again.
   There's one point, however, on which the experts agree _ serial
murder cases are tough to crack.
   ``If enough crime scene data can be collected and if you get
lucky with a national system then maybe, maybe at the sixth or
seventh killing you'll get leads,'' said Robert O. Heck, an
architect of the FBI's serial killing unit and a manager at the
Justice Department's office of juvenile justice.
   Bud Merle, executive director of the Santa Cruz (Calif.) Criminal
Justice Council, said serial killers are ``more adept at escape and
evasion measures than most criminals and their crimes tend to be
more random.''
   Levin, however, said his research indicates most serial killers
stick to familiar territory. ``In the dark world of serial killing,
the vast majority kill on a part-time basis while playing with their
kids, attending church, carrying on a relationship with their
wife,'' he said.
   Under the circumstances and given the length of time since the
last victim's skeleton was turned up, the experts said the New
Bedford murderer or murderers may never be caught.
   ``If this case is ever solved it will most likely be in a
serendipitous way. Not through some logical connection of evidence
but because the killer turns up in another city and makes a mistake
there,'' Levin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
