<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Demonstrate in Macedonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of angry workers demanding
food and more pay demonstrated for the fourth day Monday in the
Macedonian capital of Skopje.
   Sources and the state-run television said about 3,000 textile
workers were demonstrating in front of the local legislature in
downtown Skopje, chanting ``Down with the government'' and ``We want
bread.''
   It was one in a series of strikes that has hit this communist
country in the past month.
   The television said the Skopje workers refused a 100 percent pay
increase offered to them by their factory managers and demanded a
200 percent wage increase.
   Yugoslavia is faced with its worst economic and political crisis.
The annual inflation rate is about 1,000 percent and living
standards have dropped to the level of mid-1960, according to
official statistics.
   Macedonia is the poorest of Yugoslavia's six republics.
