<FIRST>r a AM-HashishShip     09-04 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hashish Ship,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Seize 25 Tons of Hash, Arrest Seven</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents seized 25 tons of Middle
Eastern hashish valued at $150 million concealed in a false
compartment aboard a boat docked on the Columbia River.
   ``It means about 1 million people won't be lighting up in the
next 60 days,'' said Lawrence A. LaDage, agent in charge of the
Customs Service in the Northwest.
   The seven men arrested in Friday's bust, the largest on the West
Coast, will be arraigned Tuesday.
   The hashish was found aboard a 158-foot converted oil-rig supply
ship that had been under surveillance for six months, LaDage said.
The vessel had just returned from its first ocean voyage and
contained no other cargo.
   The ship was believed to have been supplied by a ``mother ship''
at sea, LaDage said. Customs and the Coast Guard searched for that
vessel, he said.
   The hashish was concealed in a false compartment, LaDage said.
Agents seized the drugs as they were being unloaded in plywood
containers designed to resemble bins for oil drums.
   Agents became suspicious as soon as the oil-rig supply vessel
appeared at the out-of-the-way dock in Columbia City, LaDage said.
``We don't have any offshore rigs around here,'' he said. ``It just
didn't look right.''
   Hashish, up to five times stronger than marijuana, is produced
from the marijuana plant's resin. LaDage said the hashish was
believed to have originated in the Middle East, possibly Pakistan or
Afghanistan.
   Previously, the biggest haul on the West Coast was about 12 tons
seized several years ago in San Francisco, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
