<FIRST>u a PM-CattleDrive 1stLd-Writethru a0443 09-04 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cattle Drive, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0443,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Re-Creation of 19th Century Cattle Drive Gets Under Way</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs with cattle drive under way; PICKS UP 3rd
graf pvs, `There have ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM LACEKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROUNDUP, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Silhouetted against the rising sun, nearly
3,000 riders, 300 covered wagons and 2,700 head of cattle set out
today on a 60-mile cattle drive in honor of Montana's statehood
centennial.
   The drive began in this small community on the high plains and
will end Saturday in the stockyards of Billings.
   Steam jetted from the nostrils of horses and cattle in the crisp
morning air as the herd, bawling and protesting, began its journey
south.
   The cattle were moved by whistling and whooping drovers, clad in
bright yellow slickers and carrying lassos and bullwhips. The
animals were herded past brilliant green alfalfa fields, through a
canyon and onto the open range.
   Cowboys and the curious thronged this town of 2,200 to
commemorate the cattle drives of the late 1800s. The event is the
biggest planned for Montana's 100th birthday.
   ``There have not been this many horsemen together since the
Battle of the Little Big Horn,'' said Barry McWilliams, an
organizer. ``It is stupendous. Anybody who doesn't see this is
really going to miss it.''
   The route of the Great Montana Centennial Cattle Drive ambles
south from the Musselshell River along U.S. 87, a two-lane blacktop,
to stockyards in Billings.
   Organizers faced problems with 20th century environmental
concerns, Humane Society objections and private property rights.
   As a result, the cattle, about 85 percent longhorns, often will
be separated by several miles from the 300 or so covered wagons on
the road.
   ``Everything has turned out right,'' said trail boss Jim Stovall.
``Ranch people just do it. We are going to solve the problems. The
cowboys will do it. I didn't really realize this was going to happen
until I got up here Wednesday morning behind a load of longhorns.''
   The non-profit Latigo Corp., the sponsoring organization,
originally contemplated 10,000 cattle, 5,000 riders and 500 wagons.
But although those numbers weren't met, the celebration swelled
Roundup with visitors in cars with license plates from at least 20
states.
   By Sunday evening, beer stands were doing a steady business and
country-western bands provided entertainment.
   Several people said they were taking part in the drive because
they expect it to be a unique experience.
   ``I don't want to brag,'' said Sam Redding of Hardin, ``but we'll
never see anything like this again.''
   ``I've never done anything like this, and I don't know anybody
who has,'' said George Schiller of East Helena.
   Ellen Hargrave, who runs a ranch outside Kalispell with her
husband, Leo, took a longer view: ``I want to be a part of history.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
