<FIRST>u i PM-Iran-Hostages 2ndLd-Writethru a0521 09-04 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Hostages, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0521,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Official Says Bush Wrote Letters to Iranian Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th pvs, `Some of...,' to UPDATE with White
House comment. Pick up 5th pvs, `Fanatical Shiite...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian official said President Bush
has written letters to Iran's leaders, and that Western hostages
held in Lebanon may be freed if Washington releases Iranian assets,
Iranian news media said today.
   The comments by Deputy Foreign Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati
were based on an interview in the English-language Tehran Times and
carried by the official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia.
   Besharati claimed that Bush recently sent ``several letters'' to
Iranian leaders.
   Some of these messages, he told the daily, were ``addressed to
the Islamic Republic of Iran.'' Others, he added, were received
through the Swiss Embassy, which handles U.S. interests in Iran, and
a few through countries trying to mediate an end to the feud.
   In Kennebunkport, Maine, White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk
denied the reports, saying: ``There has been no message sent by the
president to the Iranian leadership.''
   Fanatical Shiite Moslem groups financed and supported by Iran are
believed to be holding the 16 Western hostages, including eight
Americans.
   The Iranian news agency quoted Besharati as saying ``Iran never
replied to the United States in writing,'' but that ``verbal
messages definitely were given through messengers.''
   The agency quoted him as saying the Iranian leadership feels the
Bush adminstration has realized the ``mistakes'' made by former
President Reagan's adminstration.
   ``We see the Bush adminstration has tried to undo many things of
the past,'' he added.
   The agency quoted him as adding that as ``a sign of goodwill, the
United States should denounce interference in Iranian affairs by
previous adminstrations and release the Iranian assets with no
conditions attached.
   ``If the United States stops hostility toward Iran, that will
have an impact on the entire Moslem world,'' Besharati added.
   Asked if that would help secure the release of Western hostages
in Lebanon, he said: ``Yes, I believe that the hostage issue will
also be solved and all the hostages may be released.''
   The hostages are eight Americans, four Britons, an Italian, an
Irishman and two West Germans. The longest held is American Terry
Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
