<FIRST>r p AM-Cubans-Hispanics     09-04 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cubans-Hispanics,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Cuban Representative May Not Fit in With Other Hispanics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ileana Ros-Lehtinen heads to Washington this week to
become the first Cuban-American in Congress, the latest
demonstration of the exile community's growing political power.
   But some doubt whether the conservative and fiercely
anti-communist Republican will fit in with the other Hispanic
members of Congress _ mostly liberal Democrats _ in building
influence for the nation's 20 million-plus Hispanic-Americans.
   ``The Hispanic caucus is social issues-oriented and I think
she'll have difficulty with her views,'' said Alfredo Duran, a
Cuban-born lawyer and former state Democratic chairman.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, 37, was elected a week ago to the House seat
held for 27 years by Democrat Claude Pepper before his death May 30.
She was elected almost solely on Hispanic, mostly Cuban-American,
votes after a campaign in which she accused Democrat Gerald Richman
of bigotry for his claim that he was running for ``an American
seat.''
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen will become the 12th member of the Hispanic
caucus, which is dominated by representatives of Mexican-American
and Puerto Rican descent. She will be the only Hispanic Republican
with a vote in Congress.
   Marguerita Roque, staff director of the Hispanic caucus, said in
Washington that the caucus has focused in recent years on such
issues as bilingual education, immigration, health care, getting
undocumented aliens counted in the federal census and minority
business development.
   She said the caucus, which also has 58 associate members who are
non-Hispanic, also has become more involved in U.S. foreign policy,
particularly in Central America.
   Cuban-Americans, leaving a communist homeland, have tended to
emphasize foreign policy and distrust of big government and taxes.
The average income and employment of the more than 1 million
Cuban-Americans are higher than that of other Hispanic minority
groups.
   ``Definitely, the Cubans are much more conservative than the rest
of the Hispanic community,'' said Duran.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen said during her campaign that she believes she
can explain the communist threat to other members of the Hispanic
caucus. She said her background as an educator should help as she
tries to work with Hispanics on issues of common ground.
   Some Cuban-American leaders say Ms. Ros-Lehtinen's views
represent older Cuban exile attitudes and not those of young Cubans.
   Mayor Xavier Suarez, an independent elected in 1985 as the first
Cuban-American in that job, said Ms. Ros-Lehtinen will make the Bush
administration more sensitive to Hispanic concerns and can explain
communist Cuba ``without being fanatical about it.''
   Duran said Ms. Ros-Lehtinen may help bring younger Cubans to the
Democrats.
   ``Just wait until Ileana starts casting her votes in Congress,''
Duran said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
