<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-US     09-04 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Officials Urge Japanese to Restructure Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. participants in trade talks said they urged
Japan on Monday to give its consumers a better deal by increasing
imports and changing the economic structure to bring prices down.
   ``Goods are expensive, public infrastructure is inadequate and
leisure time is scarce in Japan, even though nominal income here is
the world's highest,'' an American delegate said privately. ``We
urged the government to find ways to solve these problems and solve
them quickly.''
   American negotiators said they suggested broad changes in Japan's
land use policies, retail and wholesale distribution networks,
pricing and business practices to reduce Japan's $50 billion annual
trade surplus with the United States and improve the lives of
Japanese citizens.
   A Japanese commentator said the U.S. demands were ``like asking a
healthy person to become sick,'' but the U.S. official said: ``Steps
we suggested would be supported by increasing purchasing power for
consumers and lowering prices. We discussed a variety of ways
Japanese consumers would benefit.''
   He said Americans raised the issues of tax and zoning rules that
tend to limit land available in urban areas for residential housing
and urged the Japanese government to spend more on roads, airports,
sewers and public parks.
   In nine hours of talks Monday, the American side also argued for
changes in Japanese business practices that discriminate against
outsiders and keep prices high.
   Another U.S. official said ``keiretsu'' _ tight-knit business
networks _ and exclusive business practices prevent newcomers from
penetrating the market.
   ```Dango,' or collusion, and group boycotts are illegal but seem
to occur nonetheless,'' he said, on condition of anonymity. ``Other
practices such as `buy Japanese' procurement policies ... are not
illegal, but do make entry into the Japanese market difficult.''
   On the agenda for Tuesday are Japanese recommendations for
structural reform of the U.S. economy. Japan's delegation is
expected to press for reduction of the federal budget deficit,
increased investment in factories and greater efforts to sell
American goods abroad.
   Japanese officials said they would urge the United States to
improve vocational training programs, increase the savings rate,
strengthen drug enforcement and focus on long-term investments
rather than short-term profit.
   Negotiations on Japanese tariffs and other trade restrictions
have succeeded in reducing such barriers, but Japanese surpluses
with the United States and other industrialized countries remain
high.
   In this round of U.S.-Japanese trade talks, expected to last a
year, delegates are focusing on the need for changes in the way each
does business, educates its children and structures its society.
   Both sides are expected to find ambitious structural adjustments
politically difficult to achieve.
   During his visit to Washington last week, Prime Minister Toshiki
Kaifu said such changes must be made if the trade imbalance is to be
overcome.
   Michihiko Kunihiro, deputy foreign minister, told reporters
Monday: ``The problems are broad and socially deep-rooted, so I
can't predict at this point what degree of results can be achieved
from the talks.''
   U.S. participants in Monday's talks said they expected to have an
interim statement on the negotiations next spring and a final report
on recommendations by summer.
   ``We all think it's possible to get a concrete result,'' said
Lynn Williams, deputy U.S. trade representative and one of the
delegates.
</TEXT>
