<FIRST>r i AM-Non-aligned     09-04 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Non-aligned,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zambia Warns of South African Civil War; Arafat Blasts Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kenneth Kaunda of Zambia
said Monday that unless apartheid is ended, South Africa will be
consumed by violence so great it will make the French Revolution
``look like a children's picnic.''
   Kaunda spoke at the opening of the summit of 102 non-aligned
nations in Belgrade.
   South Africa has been gripped by a growing campaign by
anti-apartheid groups to defy segregation laws. The series of
rallies and marches, some involving violent clashes with police,
have been staged to protest the exclusion of blacks in Wednesday's
parliamentary elections.
   The Zambian leader told delegates to the non-aligned nations'
conference that ``If apartheid is not ended now, South Africa will
be enveloped by a horrendous explosion .... in which the whites who
escape will be lucky.
   ``There will be a bloodshed which will make the French
Revolution, bloody as it was, look like a children's picnic,''
Kaunda said.
   Kaunda is one of the most outspoken critics of South African
racial policies. On Aug. 28, he met with South African President
F.W. de Klerk in Zambia to discuss de Klerk's plans for ending the
black-white conflict.
   Also at Monday's meeting, PLO leader Yasser Arafat accused the
United States of refusing to respond to the Palestinian group's
peace initiatives.
   Arafat blasted the Bush administration for continuing ``to deny
our people the most elementary and important human rights, namely
the sacred right of self-determination for all peoples in the
world.''
   Despite meetings with the PLO during the last nine months, the
U.S. ``has not responded to the Palestinian peace initiative.
   ``Instead, they adopted the plan of the Israeli government to
perpetuate the Israeli control over the Palestinian land,'' the PLO
leader said.
   Arafat said Aug. 19 that the dialogue between the United States
and the Palestine Liberation Organization was deadlocked and could
fuel the 20-month-old Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied
territories.
   The United States in December ended a 13-year ban on dealings
with the PLO after Arafat renounced terrorism and recognized
Israel's right to exist.
   The non-aligned movement's ninth summit is aimed at revamping the
group to recapture its waning influence in world affairs.
   The four-day summit brought together about 50 heads of state and
about a dozen prime ministers from the Middle East, Africa, Asia and
Latin America.
   Addressing the plenary session, U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar called on Third World nations to resolve their own
conflicts, saying ``The world would be a far happier place if the
collective influence of the movement were fully brought to bear on
their settlement.''
</TEXT>
