<DOCNO> AP890904-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 1450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CanyonPollution Bjt   09-04 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canyon Pollution, Bjt,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Power Plant Linked to Haze over Grand Canyon Is Unlikely To Close</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Denis in 19th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PAGE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power plant on Indian land that supplies
electricity to three states is accused of casting a haze over the
Grand Canyon, but officials say there's little chance the plant will
be forced to close.
   Plant officials say the coal-fired plant produces power so
cheaply in comparison to oil-fired plants that there's no question
of shutting down, even if they have to install hundreds of millions
of dollars in new equipment.
   And while disputing how much the Navajo Generating Station really
affects the Grand Canyon, plant officials and nearby residents are
looking at the bright side, saying cleanup efforts are sure to bring
more jobs.
   It's the only major Southwestern power plant without scrubbers in
its smokestacks to remove pollution.
   ``We are part of the problem, but we are not the major part of
the problem,'' said Tom Hull, a control room operator. ``My parents
are involved in tourism. I don't want the Grand Canyon to be hazy.''
   The 2,250-megawatt plant, one of the largest in the country, was
built in the early 1970s on Navajo reservation land just outside
town and uses coal mined on Navajo land. The plant is 80 miles from
the center of the Grand Canyon.
   The project is owned by a group that includes the federal Bureau
of Reclamation and public and private utilities in Arizona,
California and Nevada. It is managed by the Salt River Project, a
state-federal agency.
   The owners pay to lease the Navajo land, and also pay the tribe
for the coal.
   Last week, the Environmental Protection Agency said there was
``substantial evidence'' that sulfur dioxide emissions from the
plant were reducing visibility at the Grand Canyon.
   Bob Yunke, a lawyer for the Environmental Defense Fund, said
programs under way to reduce smog in Los Angeles and control the
copper smelters in the region leave the Page plant as ``the single
major contributor to the problem.''
   Cleaning up the emissions will translate to ``approximately the
cost of a candy bar per month'' to the average customer, he added.
   The plant can generate electricity for at least $600,000 less a
day than it would cost to buy replacement power elsewhere, said
Charles Bruback, the plant's acting manager. That means even the
most expensive pollution controls _ estimates range up to $1 billion
_ would be cheaper in the long run than scrapping the plant.
   ``I would be amazed if there could be any kind of control
required of us that would make this not a viable alternative,'' he
said.
   The operation saves money because coal is cheaper than oil and
because the coal is mined so close by that it saves transportation
costs.
   ``We'll be here operating this plant as long as it has economic
life in it,'' Bruback said. ``In fact, there probably will be more
jobs because of this.''
   That's good news for the 7,190 residents of Page, built
overlooking Lake Powell on the Utah-Arizona line.
   While the population has dropped since the plant was completed,
the project is still the economic mainstay of the town. Its annual
payroll of $40 million includes more than 750 permanent employees
and up to 1,000 seasonal workers.
   ``We live and die by that plant,'' says Will Hannemann, a real
estate broker and seasonal plant worker.
   The plant also means income for the Navajos, but lease and other
payments go directly to the tribal government in Window Rock, 300
miles away. Critics complain that little of it comes back to the
Navajos living near here.
   ``There are people living a mile outside the generating station
that have no running water or electricity,' says Denis Tsosie, head
of the tribe's local government agency.
   Still, Indians derive some jobs from the plant, because its lease
gives hiring preference to Navajos. Bruback said Indians make up
about 48 percent of the permanent work force.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
