<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 1502EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush     09-04 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Back in Washington, Suited Up For Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, refreshed by nearly three weeks
in the summer hideaway he calls his ``heaven,'' returned to
Washington on Monday after proclaiming himself eager to get back to
work.
   As if to underscore that sentiment, the president left Maine
dressed casually and emerged from Air Force One at Andrews Air Force
Base barely an hour later dressed in a business suit for the final
helicopter hop to the White House.
   Bush, who broke a jinx by reeling in a bluefish Sunday, caught
two more fish in a final outing aboard his speedboat Fidelity before
he and wife Barbara boarded the Marine One helicopter at their
Walker's Point retreat to begin the journey homeward.
   Meanwhile, a White House spokesman, Roman Popadiuk, denied a
report in the Tehran Times that Bush had written personal letters to
the new leaders of Iran. ``There has been no message sent by the
president to the Iranian leadership,'' he said.
   The United States last sent a message to the government of Iran
through third parties six weeks ago, Popadiuk said. The United
States has used the Swiss embassy and other channels to communicate
with Iran in the past.
   The president's first task back at the White House was to finish
work on the nationally televised address he will deliver from the
Oval Office Tuesday night unveiling his anti-drug strategy.
   Bush, who spent 20 days in Maine at his sprawling home
overlooking the Atlantic, appeared eager to get ``back to work,'' as
he put it Sunday in an impromptu talk at services at St. Ann's
Episcopal Church.
   He told his fellow parishioners that part of his anti-drug
strategy will involve asking Americans to ``involve yourselves in
the lives of others'' and to strengthen the bonds of community life.
   The $7.8 billion anti-narcotics plan, crafted by drug policy czar
William Bennett, is expected to stiffen penalties for individual
users, expand treatment for addicts and boost aid to the Andean
countries and others to help eradicate drugs at the source.
   In launching this war against drugs, Bush is seeking to make good
on the pledge in his inaugural address that ``this scourge will
stop.''
   Bush filled his days here with jogging, golfing, boating,
horseshoes and other activities, and read David Halberstam's ``The
Summer of '49,'' a lengthy book about a classic pennant race between
the New York Yankees and Boston Red Sox.
   He also squeezed in a modicum of business, dispatching $65
million in military aid to Colombia for its war against the drug
barons; hosting visits from Danish Prime Minister Poul Schlueter and
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and their families; and
huddling with Bennett and top Cabinet officials on the drug
battleplan.
   He also found time last Wednesday to accept the 1989 Outstanding
Citizen Award from the Kennebunkport Chamber of Commerce _ the
choice was unanimous _ where he told the local boosters, ``It's been
a joy to be here.''
   ``This is a place where we really enjoy ourselves, but more than
that kind of refurbish our souls and get our batteries all charged
up and enjoy life really to the fullest,'' said Bush.
   It was actually Bush's second stay of the summer at the spot he
calls ``this heaven'' and where he has come every summer of his life
except one when he was off fighting in the Pacific.
   He is expected back again once or twice during a busy fall that
will also see him holding an education summit with governors Sept.
27-28 in Charlottesville, Va., and journeying the following month to
a Latin summit in Costa Rica.
   He has trips to at least seven states coming up in the next three
weeks, including a speech at the United Nations on Sept. 24, even
while he struggles with Congress to reach an accord on the deficit
and taxes and to unclog a backlog of nominees awaiting confirmation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
