<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     09-04 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Boycotts Meeting in Rushdie Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran boycotted a 108-nation conference of lawmakers
Monday to protest British author Salman Rushdie's novel, ``The
Satanic Verses.'' Police were investigating a bomb blast linked to
the campaign against Rushdie.
   Iran sent a message last week saying its delegation would stay
away from the conference and charging that the ``British government
under the pretext of freedom of speech'' had supported Rushdie and
encouraged publication of the book, said Inter-Parliamentary Union
spokesman Richard Faulkner.
   The Inter-Parliamentary Union meeting, which opened Monday,
prides itself on providing a forum for contacts between legislators,
often from hostile countries. Boycotts of its annual meetings are
rare.
   Iran and Britain cut diplomatic ties after Iran's Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini on Feb. 14 called on Moslems to kill Rushdie
because of the book, considered blasphemous by many Moslems.
   Since Khomeini's death June 3, Iranian authorities have stood by
the death threat. Rushdie, an Indian-born Moslem, remains in hiding
under British police guard.
   On Sunday night, a bomb exploded outside a London department
store after an anonymous caller telephoned a warning to police and
mentioned Rushdie's novel. A passer-by was injured in the blast.
   The Liberty department store, in central London's bus shopping
district, was closed at the time of the blast. It reopened for
business as usual at 9:32 a.m. Monday, only two minutes late. No
damage was caused to the store's interior and only a small scorch
was visible on the exterior.
   Until recently, the department stored housed a Penguin bookstore
concession. ``The Satanic Verses'' was published last year under the
Viking imprint, which is part of the Penguin group.
   Queen Elizabeth II on Monday opened the 100th anniversary meeting
of the Inter-Parliamentary Union before 1,400 delegates who included
members of the U.S. Congress, Soviet deputies, Israelis and Arabs.
The conference was held in the 11th-century Westminster Hall, part
of the British Houses of Parliament.
   This week's meeting was due to discuss the Third World debt and
the peaceful use of space.
</TEXT>
