<FIRST>r a AM-Brites SUB a0567 09-04 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites, SUB, a0567,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last item to delete redundant `46th annual.'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE MAY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bivalves flew like rockets at the 46th
annual clamshell pitching contest.
   The contest, loosely modeled on horseshoe-pitching competitions,
drew nearly 100 entrants Sunday.
   Dolores Houston of Levittown, Pa., won the women's singles
championship, and Art Naclerio of New York City won the men's
singles title for the third time by defeating 71-year-old Tom Spear,
the 1988 titleholder.
   ``We're just a band of folks who like to pitch shells. The best
part about the game is that anybody can play it,'' said Rich
Reinhart, president of the International Clamshell Pitching Club of
Cape May.
   Competitors toss the shells, about 4 inches in diamater, at holes
in the sand. Getting one in the hole means two points, being nearest
to the hole means a point.
   In a twist on horseshoes _ which, after all, don't break very
easily _ participants must throw broken shells until they are less
than two-thirds of their initial size.
   So what does a first-rate clamshell pitcher win?
   ``The city donates trophies and of course there's a lot of fame
and glory and bragging rights,'' Reinhart said.
</TEXT>
