<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Space     09-04 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Space,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cosmonauts to Man Space Station After 4-Month Absence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet space officials made preparations Monday for
the launch of two cosmonauts on a six-month mission to reopen the
Mir space station, which was left unmanned while the country saved
money and designed new equipment.
   Flight commander Alexander Viktorenko, 43, and 45-year-old
engineer Alexander Serebrov are scheduled to be launched from the
Baikonur space center early Wednesday morning aboard the Soyuz TM-8
craft.
   They are to dock with the Mir space station Sept. 8, the Tass
news agency said.
   On their six-month mission, the two cosmonauts are to try out a
new Soviet ``space bicycle'' to carry out work outside the orbiting
complex, and fit Mir with a docking port for the Buran space shuttle.
   As soon as Viktorenko and Serebrov are launched, preparations
will begin to send a seven-ton payload, mostly of research
equipment, to the space station, Tass said.
   Mir was launched in February 1986 and was designed to be
permanently manned, but the last crew left on April 27.
   Officials say they have left it unmanned for several months to
save money and because new modules were not ready for launch.
</TEXT>
