<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 1625EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp     09-04 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Drug Plan Has Credibility Hurdle to Clear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's new blueprint for fighting
drugs faces a credibility problem in Congress unless the
administration specifies where it plans to get the $7.8 billion he's
calling for to wage the war, says a Senate committee chairman.
   Appropriations skirmishes earlier this year over paying for
current antidrug efforts already have some lawmakers expressing
skepticism even before Bush unveils his new initiative Tuesday night.
   ``The single most important thing the president must do when he
announces his plan, whatever the cost ... is to tell us how we're
are going to pay for it and commit that we will pay for it,'' said
Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
   The biggest issues immediately facing Congress upon its return
Tuesday from a month-long vacation are a bill in the Senate
mandating that new services by provided to the disabled and
prohibiting discrimination against them and a measure in the House
to upgrade trade relations with Hungary.
   And the alleged sexual peccadilloes of four congressmen _ Reps.
Barney Frank, D-Mass.; Gus Savage, D-Ill.; Donald E. ``Buz'' Lukens,
R-Ohio, and Jim Bates, D-Calif. _ will be examined by the House
Ethics Committee.
   The overriding topic, however, will be Bush's proposed new
strategy to dam the flow of tens of billions of dollars worth of
cocaine into the United States annually and curb the appetite of
estimated 24 million Americans for it and other illegal drugs.
   Biden, who will wield considerable power over the proposal Bush
sends to Congress, has repeatedly complained that many provisions of
an anti-drug bill approved last year turned hollow from a lack of
funds.
   ``It meant hundreds of FBI agents and hundreds of DEA agents and
hundreds of treatment programs, all of which were promised to local
communities and the American people, never got into place after all
the folderol,'' he said.
   This time, he says, the money must be earmarked.
   ``It cannot be the blue smoke and mirrors of saying we are going
to reprogram,'' Biden said. ``If you're going to reprogram, tell us
precisely ... where is the money specifically going to come from.''
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu has said the $7.8 billion
in new anti-drug initiatives that Bush will advocated will be
scraped together through cuts in other programs.
   Administration officials, however, have offered no specifics. And
one officials, speaking anonymously, had said the administration
hopes to keep secret about 30 percent of the new program.
   Biden said Democrats may decide to draft their own alternative if
they don't like Bush's proposal.
   Meanwhile, both the House and Senate have a light week of floor
action facing them..
   In the Senate, lawmakers on Thursday take up a bill to provide
disabled individuals with the same rights accorded under the Civil
Rights Act of 1964 to racial, religious and ethnic minorities.
   The measure, which has bipartisan support, also requires
wheelchair access to new and modified buildings, public
transportation vehicles and terminals and mandates wider use of
telecommunications equipment for the hearing impaired.
   A day earlier, the Senate will take up a $2 billion bill for
paying the cost of running Congress for the next fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1. The House already has approved a $1.6 billion
version.
   Legislation to extend ``most favored nation'' trading status to
Hungary comes before the House on Thursday. The bill would
effectively reduce tariffs and other barriers against imports from
Hungary.
   The House then plans to act on proposed changes in laws governing
how commodity futures are traded in the aftermath of trading
scandals at the Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Among other things, the bill would prohibit approval of new
futures contracts by the federal Commodity Futures Trading
Commission if the trading pits fail to meet new auditing standards
requiring a detailed trail of transactions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
