<FIRST>r a AM-Prisoner'sPrize     09-04 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prisoner's Prize,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jail Inmate Wins $1,000 In McDonald's Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONWAY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meals for prisoners in the city jail come
from McDonald's, but that's just fine for inmate Charles E. Wilson _
he won $1,000 in a promotion run by the fast-food chain.
   ``I've never won anything,'' Wilson said Monday.
   Wilson, 33, of Brooksville, Fla., is apparently the biggest local
winner in the national McDonald's instant winner promotion, in which
game pieces are peeled from soft drink cups, said Bob Kennedy,
assistant manager of the Conway store.
   Wilson's chances of winning were 476,000-to-1, Kennedy said,
adding that the restaurant sells about 1,000 drinks a day, each
bearing a game piece.
   City officials said Wilson is apparently the only prisoner in the
jail to ever win a fast-food promotion.
   Wilson was arrested Thursday and is awaiting extradition to
Carthage, Mo., to face a charge of possession of a controlled
substance that was filed in February, a spokesman for the Jasper
County, Mo., Sheriff's Department said Monday. The extradition,
which Wilson is not fighting, should be complete in a few days,
officers said.
   On Sunday night, Wilson said he finished his meal and noticed the
game piece on his soft-drink cup.
   ``I wasn't paying any attention. I thought I might as well pull
it off, it was something to do,'' Wilson said. ``I thought maybe I'd
win a hamburger and they'd pick me up an extra one.''
   However, ``I pulled it off and said, `Do what?'
   ``I had to look at it a bunch of times. I kept thinking instant
winner, it's got to be $1,000,'' he said. ``It's pretty good to be
sitting in jail and win $1,000.''
   Wilson asked Patrolman Lynn Carter to look at the game piece.
``It said bigger than life: `instant winner of $1,000,''' the
patrolman said.
   The prisoner ``had a real big grin on his face,'' Carter said.
``He was just short of jumping up and down.''
   ``As far as I'm concerned, it's his. He pulled it off the cup,''
Carter said. ``I'm quite sure there will be no controversy over
who'll get it.
   ``He's in jail but you're still happy for him.''
   Carter said a restaurant spokesman told him forms would have to
be sent in to verify the win and allow Wilson to claim the prize
money.
   ``We told him if we had to we'd handcuff him and take him up
there,'' Carter said. ``Needless to say, he's real excited and
McDonald's is too.''
   Kennedy said it might take up to eight weeks to process the prize
claim.
   ``Too bad I won't get it in time for my lawyer,'' Wilson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
