<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0585 09-04 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0585,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Strike to Back Demand for Control of Disputed Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-10 beginning: Editors at ... with 5 grafs to UPDATE
strike in Baku with report 95 percent of factories closed. Picks up graf
11 pvs, `Food stores ...' Minor editing throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikers silenced factories, stores and public
transportation in Azerbaijan on Monday in a bid to regain their
republic's control of a region disputed with neighboring Armenia.
   In a separate ethnic dispute in the republic of Moldavia,
Russian-speaking workers stayed away from their jobs at about 200
factories and offices to protest a law making Moldavian the official
language.
   The strikes underscore the variety and severity of ethnic
problems facing President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and the country's
Communist leadership.
   The Communist Party Central Committee is scheduled to meet in
early September to debate a new approach to relations among the
Soviet Union's more than 100 ethnic groups.
   The evening television news devoted its first 15 minutes Monday
to reports from Moldavia, which borders Romania, and two Baltic
republics, Lithuania and Latvia.
   Popular movements in the Baltic area are pressing for more
autonomy from Moscow, and some activists there are pushing for
secession.
   Monday's walkout in Azerbaijan, a mainly Moslem republic on the
Caspian Sea, was called by the local People's Front political
movement.
   The strike committee claimed 95 percent of factories in the
capital of Baku, a city with 1.7 million residents, were shut by the
strike and that freight trains were halted throughout the republic,
said Nazim Ragimov, an independent journalist.
   He said that number included about 200 factories but he had no
figure for the number of people on strike. Ragimov was contacted by
telephone.
   Editors at the official Azerinform news agency said some
employees went to their factories and offices but many did not work.
Another editor reported the strike partly idled a major oil refining
and processing center on the Caspian coast.
   Food stores were the only shops open in Baku. Izmail Agayev, head
of the Azerbaijan Foreign Ministry's Information Department, said
some bus and streetcar drivers also walked out.
   He did not estimate how many people were on strike.
   The People's Front has made several demands, including the recall
of representatives to the national Congress of People's Deputies,
who they say were chosen in fraudulent balloting and did nothing in
the parliament's first session.
   They also demand that Azerbaijan reassert control over
Nagorno-Karabakh, a mountainous enclave. It is 75 percent ethnic
Armenian, although it lies in Azerbaijan.
   Armenia wants to annex it, and the Kremlin has put it under
direct rule to try to end the dispute.
   The dispute has killed 100 people and forced hundreds of
thousands to flee their homes.
   Krasnaya Zvezda, the Defense Ministry newspaper, said Sunday that
tensions between Armenia and Azerbaijan ``are like gunpowder,'' and
that Nagorno-Karabakh is on the verge of civil war.
   The strikes in predominantly Russia-speaking regions of Moldavia,
which began late last month, continued Monday when workers rejected
a language compromise worked out in the republic's Supreme Soviet
legislature. The compromise made Moldavian the official language but
did not impose it as the language that must be used by all ethnic
groups.
   Strikers demand that the republic's 4.2 million people, 64
percent of whom are ethnic Moldavians, have two official languages:
Russian and Moldavian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890904-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 1754EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CattleDrive     09-04 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cattle Drive,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head 'Em Up ... Move 'Em Out! Cattle Drive Begins 60-Mile Trail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM LACEKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROUNDUP, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Great Montana Centennial Cattle Drive
began Monday in the golden light of sunrise as the lead longhorns
crested a ridge in single file and then all 2,700 animals formed an
undulating, bawling river of beef.
   The six-day, 60-mile journey from this small community on the
high plains of eastern Montana to the stockyards of Billings is the
largest spectacle in Montana's year-long celebration of its birthday
as a state.
   The cattle, herded by a band of 105 drovers, was joined south of
here by a contingent of about 300 covered wagons and 3,000 riders
prepared to spend the next week on the trail.
   Shortly before daybreak, the cattle were headed up east of town
along the Musselshell River where they had been bedded down
overnight.
   As the sun broke over the horizon and lightened the clear sky,
the first longhorns trotted over the hill. Steam jetted from the
nostrils of cows and horses in the crisp air and the cattle kicked
up a haze of dust that drifted through the morning light.
   Whistling and whooping drovers in bright yellow slickers and
waving lassos and bullwhips, urged the complaining, reluctant herd
southward into a small canyon and between fields of brilliant green
alfalfa.
   From there, the cattle were moved onto open range.
   At late morning, cheers greeted the sight of huge longhorns being
herded through Roundup, leading the miles of wagons and riders
toward their rendezvous with the main herd.
   Stomping and snorting in confusion, one group of the animals
turned onto Main Street where they were met with thousands of
spectators lining the mile-long route. The crowd shied away from the
steers, each standing about six feet tall with horns spanning as
much as five feet.
   The people cheered and applauded many of the riders and wagons,
and cheered and rose to their feet, hands over their hearts, when
the first of several flags finally appeared in the parade column.
   Riders on horseback and in wagons took on the appearance of their
Old West forerunners, except in their desire to record the event.
Many trained their video cameras on the other wagons and the crowd.
   The first day of the cattle drive was marred by only one serious
injury.
   Buck Draper, a cook from Colorado Springs, Colo., suffered a hip
injury when his horse reared over backwards and fell on him, said
Musselshell County Sheriff Brian Neidhardt. He was flown by
helicopter to a Billings hospital.
   The re-creation of an Old West drive will climax with another
parade when the cattle arrive in Billings on Saturday.
   On the trail, the horse and wagon riders will eat catered meals
and be entertained nightly by country-western performers.
   Trucks will bring 200,000 gallons of water and 70 tons of hay
each day to the animals.
   Montana's erractic end-of-summer weather, which can range from
driving rain to broiling heat, remains the greatest threat to the
drive. Forecasts call for rain and cooler temperatures for most of
the week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
