<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0598 09-04 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0598,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Underground Palestinian Leaders Criticize United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with attack on army truck and move
up grafs 13-16 `In clashes ... with Israel.' Picks up graf 3 pvs, `In a
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Palestinian uprising said Monday
the United States was stalling efforts for peace, and they urged
residents of the West Bank and Gaza Strip to escalate the revolt
against Israeli occupation.
   Israeli newspapers said U.S. officials were angered by lack of
progress and had told Israel they might support Egyptian demands for
concessions in Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's peace plan.
   Israeli soldiers imposed a curfew on Talluza, a West Bank village
35 miles north of Jerusalem, after residents stoned an army truck
and set it afire, military and Arab sources reported.
   The truck driver, said to have lost his way, escaped and fled to
a nearby army base. Soldiers later entered the village, and Arab
sources said they were searching for those who attacked the truck.
   Arab hospital sources said 20 Palestinians in the occupied
territories were wounded Monday by lead or plastic bullets shot by
soldiers.
   Since the uprising began 21 months ago, 557 Palestinians have
been killed by Israeli soldiers or civilians and 39 Israelis have
died. At least 106 Palestinians have been slain by fellow Arabs who
accused them of collaborating with Israel.
   In a leaflet distributed in the Israeli-occupied lands Monday,
the uprising's underground leaders accused the United States of
``regressing'' in talks with the leadership of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   It said ``the American obstinancy is blocking tangible progress
in a peace settlement.''
   The United States began talks with the PLO in December after the
group recognized Israel and renounced terrorism. That stategy,
spearheaded by PLO chief Yasser Arafat, seemed to rest on persuading
the United States to pressure on Israel to make concessions for
peace.
   But the leaflet said the lack of progress ``casts serious doubts
among the rank-and-file of our people about the usefulness of the
U.S.-PLO dialogue.''
   It added: ``Facing these obstacles, our people have no choice but
to escalate the uprising, the only option for reaching freedom and
independence.''
   Israel radio said, meanwhile, that U.S. Ambassador William Brown
told Israeli officials last week Secretary of State James A. Baker
III was ``favorably disposed'' to Egypt's stand on the Shamir plan
for elections in the occupied territories.
   The plan, put forward in April, calls for electing Palestinians
to open talks with Israel on interim autonomy for the territories.
   President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt raised 10 points related to the
plan that essentially demand such Israeli concessions as agreeing to
trading occupied land for peace and allowing the 140,000 Arabs of
east Jerusalem to vote.
   Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc has ruled out either step. But the
left-of-center Labor Party, which is a partner with Likud in the
coalition government, has accepted both moves.
   American diplomats were not available to comment on the reports
because of the Labor Day holiday.
   In their leaflet, the uprising leaders called for residents of
the occupied lands to ``refrain from rash decisions'' about
suspected collaborators and consult uprising leaders before warning
or punishing them.
   A similar appeal in a leaflet distributed Aug. 15 had no effect.
   There have been reports Israeli security forces are arming
collaborators, and the Hebrew daily Maariv said Monday that the
Arabs were receiving military training in use of weapons.
</TEXT>
