<FIRST>r i AM-NIreland-Soldier     09-04 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NIreland-Soldier,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldier Convicted of Giving Information to Radicals Now Instructs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers in Northern Ireland
expressed anger Monday that a soldier convicted of providing
information that could be of use to terrorists is now an army
instructor in England.
   Cpl. Cameron Hastie, 23, of the 1st Battalion of the Royal Scots,
was given an 18-month suspended jail sentence in Belfast Crown Court
last year after being convicted of giving information to the Ulster
Volunteer Force, an outlawed Protestant group.
   The disclosure of Hastie's job as an instructor followed a recent
case in which Protestant extremists claimed they used security-force
information to select the man they killed Aug. 25.
   The Ulster Freedom Fighters said they obtained security force
documents that identified Loughlin Maginn as a member of the
outlawed Irish Republican Army. Ulster Freedom Fighters gunmen
killed Maginn in his house. His family denied he had ties to the IRA.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to unite Northern
Ireland, a British province where protestants outnumber Catholics
3-2, with the predominantly Catholic Republic of Ireland. Protestant
terrorists determined to keep Northern Ireland in the United Kingdom
are battling the IRA extremists.
   A British army spokesman in Northern Ireland, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, confirmed that Hastie had returned to duty
and had been appointed as an instructor at a training base in
England. He refused to say which base.
   ``I do not believe that anyone convicted of offenses should ever
be allowed to serve in the security forces again. I am appalled,''
said John Alderdice, leader of the centrist Alliance Party that has
both Protestant and Catholic supporters.
   Ken Maginnis of the largely Protestant Official Unionist Party
said Hastie's return to duty showed ``a degree of contempt to the
entire community in Northern Ireland.''
   Northern Ireland Minister John Cope has said that any member of
the army or police found guilty of passing information to terrorists
could expect to suffer the ``full severity of the law.''
   The Ulster Freedom Fighters is a code name for the Ulster Defense
Association, a group founded in 1971 to coordinate paramilitary
groups that favor British rule in Northern Ireland.
</TEXT>
