<FIRST>u a AM-LewisTelethon 1stLd-Writethru a0612 09-04 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lewis Telethon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0612,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Entertainers Join Jerry Lewis For 24th Annual Telethon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with total cash and pledges raised,
quotes, details on participants; picks up 5th graf pvs: `Wedemeyer, of
...; ADDS 4 grafs quotes from deBakey, stars listed.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 24th annual Jerry Lewis Labor Day Telethon
wrapped up Monday with the comic coaxing $42,209,727 in cash and
pledges from about 100 million viewers.
   Corporations contributed an additional $36,228,846 during the
21{-hour event, which featured a parade of top name entertainers and
poignant stories from muscular dystrophy victims and their families
to push the total telethon donations since 1966 to $526,524,210.
   Lewis opened the show Sunday night by saying that inroads had
been made against 40 neuromuscular diseases that the Muscular
Dystrophy Association is involved in fighting. Lewis called the
advances ``stunning to the heart, stunning to the mind.''
   As in previous years, it was the victims and their families who
provided the telethon's most affecting moments.
   United Airlines executive Bob Sampson drew a standing ovation
from 2,000 people in the Jerry Lewis Theater at the Cashman Field
Center when he said: ``There's been enough of this disease killing
children and devastating families.''
   Sampson, who has suffered from muscular dystrophy since he was a
teen-ager and has lost two grandchildren to the disease, appeared in
a poignant appeal and encouraged viewers to keep up the fight until
the disease is beaten.
   Sampson told Lewis last week he would rather not be on the
telethon this year because it was too hard on him emotionally. Lewis
said he persuaded Sampson to return because he has been an
inspiration in the annual event.
   Lewis was moved to tears when former high school football coach
Charlie Wedemeyer, the subject of the TV movie ``Quiet Victory,''
told the audience, ``You never know which dollar it will be to make
the difference and win the fight.''
   Wedemeyer of Los Gatos, Calif., is paralyzed by amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis, also known as Lou Gehrig's disease. He conveyed
his message through his wife, Lucy, who read his lips.
   ``So often I feel I am a prisoner in my own body that has been
given a life sentence,'' Wedemeyer said. ``But I have chosen, with
God's help, to turn this disadvantage into an advantage.''
   The Oak Ridge Boys stopped the show Sunday when they introduced
11-year-old Bradley Thomas Walker of Huntsville, Ala., the Alabama
poster child for the Muscular Dystrophy Association. They then sang
their hit ``Elvira,'' with the child.
   Lewis has been a spokesman for the New York City-based Muscular
Dystrophy Association for 40 years, conducting the annual Labor Day
telethons for the benefit of ``Jerry's Kids'' since 1966.
   The telethons have raised more than $500 million from individual
donors and hundreds of millions more in corporate contributions that
are not included in the telethon totals.
   Lewis said last week that the 1989 telethon would have a special
meaning. This spring, Lewis, 63, and his 38-year-old wife, Sam,
learned she was pregnant, then were told May 5 that the fetus' heart
had stopped beating.
   Mrs. Lewis was two months pregnant at the time. Lewis has six
sons by a previous marriage.
   Famed heart surgeon Michael DeBakey of Houston said great strides
are being made to find the cause and cure for muscular dystrophy.
   ``The future is so optimistic, so great,'' DeBakey said. ``I
think it's wonderful that the American people can be assured that
the money given to this great cause will find a solution and
eliminate the disease.''
   More than 50 top-name entertainers were featured on this year's
show, including Tony Orlando, Frank Sinatra, Liza Minnelli, Sammy
Davis Jr., Billy Crystal, Alabama, the Oak Ridge Boys, Jack Jones,
Robert Goulet, the McGuire Sisters, LaToya Jackson, Ringo Starr,
Waylon Jennings and Maureen McGovern.
   Co-hosts included Davis, Orlando, Ed McMahon, Casey Kasem, Julius
La Rosa and Norm Crosby.
</TEXT>
