<HEAD>Panama's Noriega Sends Message to Libya's Gadhafi</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama-US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi received a message from Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega during a meeting with two daughters of the
Panamanian leader, the official Libyan news agency reported Monday.
   JANA, monitored in Rome, said Noriega's daughters were in Libya
to take part in ceremonies Friday marking the 20th anniversary of
the coup that brought Gadhafi to power.
   It did not say when the meeting took place. After anniversary
festivities, Gadhafi went to Yugoslavia for the meeting of the
non-aligned movement.
   JANA said the women delivered a ``written letter from their
father,'' who as chief of Panama's Defense Forces is the most
powerful individual in that country. The agency did not elaborate.
   In a later dispatch, JANA said Lorina Noriega told the agency
Panamanians regarded Gadhafi as ``the best example in the struggle
for liberation and independence.''
   She said the Panamanian people ``appreciates highly the role of
the great Al-Fatah (Libyan) revolution in supporting it against the
plots concocted by U.S. imperialism,'' JANA reported.
   Gadhafi declared his support for the Central American country in
a speech Friday.
   Noriega has been in conflict with the U.S. government since last
year. Noriega denies U.S. charges against him of drug dealing.
Washington refused to recognize a new president named by Panama's
Council of State, which is considered to be under Noriega's control.
   Gadhafi also has been in conflict with the United States, which
bombed Libya in 1986 to retaliate for what it called Libyan support
of terrorism.
