<FIRST>r i AM-Alps-Environment     09-04 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alps-Environment,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Say Tourism Destroying Alps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 million travelers visit the Alps each
year and may destroy them by the next century, two environmental
groups said Monday.
   ``The main problem is too much tourism and the departure of
agriculture,'' said Martin Holdgate, head of the Switzerland-based
World Conservation Union. He urged tourists to ``behave in less
damaging ways.''
   Pollution by cars and other means, littering and off-trail skiing
are major dangers, said a survey by Holdgate's group and the
International Center for Alpine Environments, based in France.
Forest damage and soil erosion are among the serious consequences,
the report said.
   According to the survey, the number of hotel beds and visiting
cars continues to rise and the use of lifts serving 41,000 ski
trails increases by about 5 percent annually.
   ``If you have too many people visiting the Alps, the way it is
today, there will be no Alps to visit in the next century,'' said
Dominique Rambaud of the French organization.
   He said the French resort area around Albertville, where the 1992
Winter Olympics will be held, is under ``particular pressure.''
   About 12 million people live in the Alps and more than 100
million visit every year, 60 percent of them for a day or weekend,
the survey said.
   It recognized tourism as an economic mainstay for many areas and
said one solution was to promote its less damaging forms, such as
cross-country skiing, hiking and camping.
</TEXT>
