<FIRST>r i AM-Finland-Memoirs     09-04 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Finland-Memoirs,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memoirs Allege Moscow Interfered In Finnish Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former prime minister said in memoirs
published Monday that as recently as 1981, a Russian diplomat
offered to try to influence Finland's presidential election.
   The memoirs ``clearly show the extent of Finnish-Soviet
relations. What was talked and whispered about before is now set
here before our eyes, in black and white,'' said Jukka Tarkka,
editor and co-writer of the book.
   ``The Minister of the President,'' by Center Party politician
Ahti Karjalainen, says that Viktor Vladimirov, a diplomat at the
Soviet Embassy, offered to help Karjalainen win the presidency.
   He says Vladimirov told Paavo Vayrynen, who was then Finland's
foreign minister, that ``he would like to continue to work hard'' so
Karjalainen could succeed longtime President Urho Kekkonen, who had
announced his retirement because of ill health.
   Vayrynen, chairman of the Center Party, related the conversation
in a letter to Karjalainen.
   ``Vladimirov had openly asked Vayrynen how the Soviet Union could
promote my election. He told Vayrynen that he would influence the
Communists and other political parties to support my position,''
Karjalainen wrote.
   Excerpts of the book were first published in a magazine last
week, causing a stir in normally placid Finnish politics.
   Vayrynen denied he acted against the interests of Finland or of
President Mauno Koivisto, who opposed Karjalainen as the Social
Democratic candidate and who won the 1982 election.
   Vayrynen said he spoke to the Soviet diplomat as party leader and
not as a government minister. Legal experts said, however, that
Vayrynen also represented his country and could be accused of a
treasonous act.
   The former foreign minister, who now is opposition leader, said
it was common practice at that time to discuss such matters with the
Soviets, although that had changed since then.
   Finland, defeated in war, was coerced into signing a friendship
treaty with the Soviet Union in 1948. Though officially neutral, its
caution to avoid antagonizing the Soviets gave birth to the word
``Finlandization,'' generally used to describe the subservience of a
small country to a greater power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
