<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     09-04 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Seeks to Reopen Iran-Iraq Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Non-Aligned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar met Monday with Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati in an effort to get the stalled Iran-Iraq peace talks going
again.
   Perez de Cuellar, in Belgrade for a summit conference of the
non-aligned movement, is scheduled to meet with Iraqi Foreign
Minister Tariq Aziz before leaving Wednesday.
   ``We are ready to continue our trilateral talks, I mean the
(U.N.-Iran-Iraq) peace talks, under the supervision of the
secretary-general, any time, any place,'' Velayati told reporters
after the meeting.
   Perez de Cuellar said the talks were based on U.N. Resolution 598
that calls for the withdrawal of Iraq's and Iran's troops to
internationally recognized borders and the exchange of prisoners of
war.
   Velayati said the secretary-general's latest proposal calls for
the withdrawal of Iraqi forces from Iranian territory and the
repatriation of the POWs.
   ``We welcome the proposal and are waiting for the result of the
meeting the secretary-general is going to have with the other
side,'' Velayati said. ``It is a pity that innocent people, the
POWs, from both sides are still (held) there. We do hope we could
repatriate all of them as soon as possible after withdrawal of the
Iraqi troops.''
   Velayati said about 50,000 Iraqi POWs have been registered and
29,000 Iranians held by Iraq have been registered as POWs.
   Iraq's Foreign Ministry said 10 months ago it had a list of
25,000 unregistered Iranian POWs, according to Velayati.
   He said that list has not been handed over to the International
Committee of the Red Cross.
   ``We say the first step of repatriation is the registration of
(all) Iranian POWs in Iraq,'' said Velayati. ``On the basis of
humanitarian considerations, Iran is ready to repatriate all from
both sides, immediately after the withdrawal of Iraqi forces from
Iranian territory.''
   He said the troop withdrawals could take place in two weeks while
repatriation of the POWs would take 90 days.
   Iran and Irag went to war in September 1980 following border
clashes. Fighting ended in August 1988 under a U.N.-arranged
cease-fire.
</TEXT>
