<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 2148EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BakkerTrial     09-04 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bakker Trial,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors Report To Court For Instructions on Bakker's Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors head back to federal court Tuesday
to learn whether PTL founder Jim Bakker is competent to continue his
trial for fraud and conspiracy.
   The TV evangelist spent Labor Day confined for psychiatric
examination in the Federal Correctional Institute mental health unit
in Butner, about 100 miles northeast of here, on the orders of U.S.
District Judge Robert Potter.
   ``It's still a little bit up in the air,'' Bakker's psychiatrist,
Dr. Basil Jackson, said Monday in a telephone interview from
Milwaukee. ``I haven't been given the green light yet to go and see
him.''
   Bakker, anxious and disheveled with chains on his hands and legs,
was escorted by federal marshals to Butner after Jackson testified
Bakker was hallucinating and hiding his head under a couch in his
attorney's office.
   Potter suspended Bakker's trial pending a determination of
whether the TV evangelist is competent to stand trial. The jurors
were not told about Bakker's condition, but were told to check with
the court on Tuesday to see whether court proceedings would continue
Wednesday.
   Jackson said he was told psychiatrists at Butner were speeding up
their evaluation of Bakker's emotional state over the weekend.
   ``If that's true, then it's conceivable one of their people could
come back into court Tuesday or Wednesday to certify that he's
(Bakker) ready to come back into trial,'' he said.
   Attempts on Monday to reach administrators at Butner were
unsuccessful, and attorneys and others in the case are forbidden to
discuss it under a gag order issued by Potter.
   Dr. Sally Johnson, chief of psychiatric services at Butner, has
said evaluations of patients like Bakker typically last 30 days but
could take 45 days or more.
   Jackson, who said he has not been allowed to talk with Bakker
since his arrival at Butner, said he has been in daily contact by
phone with Bakker's wife, Tammy Faye Bakker, and Bakker's attorneys
for news on his condition.
   Jackson also said he has heard Bakker has tried to contact him
daily.
   ``I think that he has settled down and certainly has improved a
lot from the way he was Thursday morning,'' Jackson said.
   ``I continue to be impressed with the emotional strength of this
man and his resilience.''
   He said it was possible Bakker would be ready to return to court
this week.
   ``I'd like to see what condition he's in and have an opportunity
to make a clinical judgment as to the likelihood of whether he might
have a similar reaction to stress in the days ahead,'' Jackson said.
   ``I'm interested not in his ability to be competent to withstand
trial on one day but competent for the entire trial,'' the
psychiatrist said.
   Bakker is charged with 24 counts of fraud and conspiracy and
faces 120 years and prison and more than $5 million in fines.
Prosecutors say Bakker used nearly $4 million in ministry funds to
finance a lavish lifestyle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
