<HEAD>Iowa Crewman Recants Testimony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sailor from the USS Iowa said Navy
investigators browbeat him into implicating one of his shipmates as
a suicidal homosexual who may have been responsible for the
explosion that killed 47 crewmen, according to a report broadcast
Monday.
   In an interview with ABC News, Seaman David Smith said he
believed that Gunner's Mate Clayton Hartwig did not cause the
explosion that destroyed one of the battleship's gun turrets.
   According to reports earlier this summer, Smith told naval
investigators that Hartwig had made sexual advances to him the night
before the April 19 explosion and that on other occasions Hartwig
had talked about how to set off explosions and showed him a timer
device.
   ``Part of me can see him doing it,'' Smith was quoted as saying.
   Hartwig died in the explosion with the other sailors.
   In his ABC News interview, Smith said the investigators
questioned him in sessions lasting up to 12 hours and threatened to
charge him with 47 counts of murder and accessory to murder if he
did not cooperate.
   Smith said investigators put words into his mouth and distorted
his testimony, ABC said.
   Navy spokesman Kendall Pease said he was unaware of the ABC
report and had no comment.
