<HEAD>Foiled Robber Fatally Wounded by Police, Hostage Unharmed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto RIO2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A robber with two revolvers who
grabbed a hostage was fatally wounded in a bungled police operation,
according to press accounts Monday.
   Luis Fernando de Souza, who held a hotel worker hostage for more
than an hour, died at a hospital Sunday just hours after being shot,
newspapers said.
   Police refused comment on the reports, which were carried in most
Rio dailies.
   According to O Globo newspaper, Souza tried to rob the Santa
Comba hotel in downtown Rio but police arrived before he could
escape.
   Souza then reportedly took Francisco Lima Barbosa hostage, held a
gun to his head and demanded police give him a getaway car.
   ``The bandit was drugged and practically leaning on me. It
appeared he couldn't stand. But his finger was firmly on the
trigger,'' Barbosa said.
   While a police official negotiated with Souza, two other officers
quietly approached from behind, the newspaper said.
   Just as one policemen prepared to tackle Souza, however, a second
fired his gun from 30 feet away, accidentally wounding another
officer in the leg, O Globo reported.
   Souza then released his hostage and, firing his guns, tried to
run to nearby hotel.
   About 20 police officers opened fire as Souza fled, fatally
wounding him, O Globo said.
