<FIRST>u i AM-StuntCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0646 09-04 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stunt Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0646,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Show Fliers Dip Wings to Salute Pilot of Downed Jet, Body Recovered</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, `Divers found...' to CORRECT that body found
on lake bottom. Picks up graf 6 pvs, `Witnesses said ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fliers at a national air show dipped airplane
wings in salute to a dead comrade Monday following an accident
involving the Snowbirds, the Canadian Forces aerobatic team.
   Two red-and-white jets of the team appeared to touch during a
complicated maneuver on Sunday and plunged into Lake Ontario a few
hundred yards from Toronto's waterfront exhibition grounds where
70,000 spectators watched the mishap.
   Maj. Dan Dempsey of Edmonton, Alberta, the 36-year-old commander
of the precision flying team, ejected safely but Capt. Shane Antaya,
24, of Stratford, Ontario, was still in his aircraft when it
nosedived into the water.
   Antaya's wife, mother, brother and sister were watching from the
shoreline, Col. Claude Thibault told reporters.
   Divers found Antaya's body on the bottom of the lake near the
wreckage of his CT-114 Tutor training jet shortly before the Monday
afternoon show began. Witnesses said he steered his crippled plane
away from a crowd of boats gathered to watch the show.
   Hillary Forrest of Toronto was on one of the hundreds of boats
near where Antaya's plane crashed.
   She said he appeared to go straight into the lake ``to avoid the
boats. It was so straight down there was no attempt to pull out
whatsoever.''
   June Kirby, a spokeswoman for the Canadian National Exhibition
air show, said it was the wish of other fliers to go on with the
third and last day of show.
   ``I think they wanted to go up there and fly the very best they
could as a tribute to Shane,'' she said.
   Thibault said the seven-member Snowbirds canceled their 15
remaining shows for 1989 and the Canadian Forces was investigating.
   Dempsey was released from Toronto General Hospital after
treatment for facial cuts and leg burns.
   The accident occurred midway through the team's performance,
during a stunt called an upward-downward bomb burst. In the
maneuver, two groups of planes fly past each other at 375 mph.
   Witnesses said the two planes appeared to touch and they tumbled
out of the tight formation. Videotape seemed to confirm the
collision.
   The Snowbirds perform more than 60 shows a year throughout North
America and have had three accidents in which two pilots were killed.
   ``We have flown in 980 shows before 60 million people,'' Thibault
said. ``Our record speaks for itself.''
   Ms. Kirby said that at a morning briefing Monday, the fliers _
from North America and Canada _ paused for a moment of silence for
Antaya. The pilots, flying everything from vintage biplanes to the
latest in jet fighters and bombers, unanimously decided to return to
the skies.
   ``It's a tradition that the pilots have the final say about
whether the show goes on,'' she said.
</TEXT>
