<FIRST>r a AM-BeachedWhale     09-04 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beached Whale,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Search for Milk Substitute for Baby Sperm Whale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine workers searched for hours Monday
before the found the right milk substitute to feed a week-old,
900-pound baby sperm whale found floundering in shallow waters this
weekend.
   The whale, dubbed Odie, was found beached Saturday west of Sabine
Pass and taken by flatbed truck the next day, covered with sunscreen
and wet cloths, to Sea Arama Marine World in Galveston.
   ``He's OK. He's just kind of sitting there'' in his holding tank,
Sea Arama spokeswoman Christy Benson said Monday. ``He now needs
some nourishment. He's a big guy _ and he's just a baby.''
   Odie is estimated to be a little more than a week old, but
already is 13 feet long. ``We don't know why he beached himself,''
Ms. Benson said, adding that most whales become stranded because
they are ill.
   Experts nationwide were contacted for help on caring for Odie
because a sperm whale has never been captive long enough to study,
said Gina Barron, coordinator for the Texas Mammal Stranding
Network, which rescued the whale.
   Marine workers have been feeding the whale an electrolyte
solution through a stomach tube to keep him hydrated, but the mammal
also needs ``caloric intake,'' Ms. Benson said.
   Sea Arama officials had trouble finding a lactose-free milk
substitute for Odie because many businesses were closed for the
Labor Day holiday, but finally found the right veterinary product at
the Houston Zoo, she said.
   Zoo officials ``brought us what they had'' for the whale, Ms.
Benson said. They also told Sea Arama officials where they could
find more Tuesday. The whale's first scheduled ``milk'' feeding was
planned Monday evening.
   ``We're just going to continue to treat him and feed him and hope
for the best,'' she said.
   Laboratories closed because of the Labor Day holiday also have
delayed efforts to find out what's wrong with the whale, she said.
   Odie's move to the marine park Sunday was delayed almost 19 hours
to make sure another whale, possibly the mother, was not in the
area. But no other whale was found, Ms. Benson said.
</TEXT>
