<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Palestinians     09-04 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Palestinians,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abu Nidal Announces Execution of 15 Arabs As Spies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The radical Palestinian group headed by
terrorist mastermind Abu Nidal said Monday it executed 15 Arabs,
including a woman, as alleged spies for the United States and other
governments.
   Younis Amran, spokesman for the Fatah-Revolutionary Council
group, said the 15 were convicted of ``spying and collaboration'' in
separate trials since November 1987.
   He said the group, comprising 11 Palestinians, two Egyptians, an
Iraqi and a Lebanese, were executed at midnight Sunday ``inside and
outside Palestine.'' He refused to say where.
   Amran said two of those executed worked for the United States and
British intelligence, two for West Germany, two for Egypt, three for
Iraq and six for Jordan.
   He said they all worked under cover with various Palestinian
guerrilla groups but Fatah-Revolutionary Council ``managed to arrest
them before they penetrated our organization.''
   The report came 10 days after a ranking Abu Nidal aide was shot
dead on Aug. 25 in south Lebanon's port of Sidon.
   The Abu Nidal group threatened last week to execute 15 detainees
to avenge the assassination of Rabah Abdul-Rahim.
   Abu Nidal is the nom de guerre of Sabri al-Banna, who split with
Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat in 1973.
   Amran, who spoke at a news conference in West Beirut's Mar Elias
Palestinian refugee camp, refused to confirm or deny that the
executions were in retaliation for Abdul-Rahim's assassination.
   Sources in Sidon said on condition of anonymity that those
executed belonged to a breakaway faction of Abu Nidal's group.
