<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 2308EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LaborDay 2ndLd-Writethru a0629 09-04 0863</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Labor Day, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0629,0881</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parades, Picnics and Protests Wind Up Summer Fun</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add pow-wow; SUBS 4th graf, bgng `By midday
...,' to UPDATE; INSERTS new grafs 8-10, `Labor Day ...,' adding teachers
strikes and walkout against Ohio union; SUBS grafs 12-16, `Michigan Gov.
..., with four grafs to UPDATE and raise reference to Detroit parade for
transition, CORRECT spelling of `protesters,' add pow-wow and tighten;
pickup 16th graf pvs, bgng `About 400...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking telephone workers bargained on Labor Day and striking
pilots protested, but for other workers the informal end to summer
was a day for parades and picnics, politicians and fireworks.
   There were also non-labor annual traditions, like the mass walk
across Michigan's 4{-mile Mackinac Bridge, an Indian pow-wow on New
York's Long Island, and the Fred Coleman Memorial Shoot, a pigeon
shoot at Hegins, Pa., that drew animal rights protesters.
   And it was a day to hit the beach. Temperatures near the 70s and
sunshine sent people streaming to recreational areas such as
Massachusetts' Cape Cod, where police reported traffic tie-ups.
   Water temperature of 66 degrees and 2- to 3-foot waves attracted
big crowds to Southern California beaches, including Muscle Beach,
which lived up to its name with a bodybuilders' competition.
   The annual Greater Boston Labor Council breakfast drew striking
Eastern Airlines and New England Telephone Co. workers, as well as
such political figures as Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   Steve Early, a spokesman for the Communications Workers of
America, said talks with New England Telephone's parent company,
NYNEX Corp., continued on the holiday and the union was hitting
holiday events throughout the region to urge people not to pay their
phone bills.
   NYNEX also negotiated Monday with the International Brotherhood
of Electrical Workers. The CWA and IBEW have been on strike since
Aug. 6, when 60,000 workers walked off the job.
   Labor Day negotiations appeared unlikely to avert a strike
Tuesday in Sacramento, Calif., by 2,500 teachers. They and teachers
in San Jose, Calif., and Coeur d'Alene, Idaho, prepared to join
counterparts in four other states in strikes affecting 119,000
students.
   In Columbus, Ohio, the state's largest teachers union was the
target of a strike. Some of about 60 secretaries and janitors spent
Labor Day picketing the Ohio Education Association in the fourth day
of a walkout over pay.
   ``This is not the what we wanted to be doing today,'' said Inez
Hott, the union's administrative assistant. ``We should be out
picnicking. Everyone had a lot plans killed because of this. But
we're dedicated.''
   United Mine Workers President Richard L. Trumka was named Citizen
of the Year by the Catholic Labor Institute of Southern California
at its 43rd annual Labor Day Breakfast in Los Angeles. Some UMW
members have been on strike against Pittston Coal Group Inc. since
April in a bitter dispute over wages and benefits.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo led mine workers, airline machinists,
telephone company employees and thousands of other union members and
their supporters in a parade up New York City's Fifth Avenue.
   ``Really what we're trying to do is just band together _ strength
in numbers,'' said parade participant Ralph Paugh, a United Mine
Worker from Shady Spring, W.Va.
   Also marching in the parade were supporters of the Polish union
Solidarity carrying banners reading: ``Help Poland Now.'' Piotr
Stasinski, a Warsaw native living temporarily in New York, said
Poland has a massive economic crisis to overcome and needs help from
the West.
   An estimated 100,000 people marched in Detroit's Labor Day
parade. Its theme was ``Michigan Works Best When We Say Union Yes,''
and United Auto Workers President Owen Bieber was one of three grand
marshals.
   Michigan Gov. James Blanchard and his bride, married Saturday,
led about 60,000 people on the traditional Labor Day trek across the
Mackinac Bridge across the Straits of Mackinac connecting Lakes
Huron and Michigan.
   About 8,000 people attended the final day of a three-day pow-pow
on the Shinnecock Indian reservation in Southampton, N.Y. The 43rd
annual pow-wow was dedicated to the memory of its founder, Chief
Thunder Bird, also known as Henry Bess, who died in June.
   More than 300 Indians representing about 70 tribes took part in
tribal dances, chants, and smoking a peace pipe.
   About 400 animal rights activists marched, chanted and screamed
at competitors in the 55th annual Fred Coleman Memorial Shoot in
Pennsylvania. Birds were released one at a time from cages about 20
yards in front of competitors with shotguns. Organizers of the
community fund-raiser had 6,000 birds on hand.
   Community members said the event is a place for family
fellowship. Between volleys, children are sent to collect dead birds
and dispatch wounded ones by pulling off their heads or wringing
their necks.
   ``You have to be a sportsman to understand,'' said Keith
Wolfgang, who has attended the event for 12 years.
   ``These protesters have their priorities mixed up,'' said Joe
Coulter. ``These people are burning flags and are in line for
abortions. It's just un-American.'' ``It's just a pure bloodsquirt
and a real slaughter,'' said protester Bob Witkowski of
Wilkes-Barre, Pa. Other protesters came from as far away as Florida
and Illinois.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
