<FIRST>r a AM-TeachersStrikes 1stLd-Writethru a0658 09-04 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teachers Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 100,000 Students Affected by Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE number of students affected; SUBS 11th graf,
bgng `In Michigan ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with new strike; pickup
12th graf pvs, bgng `Negotiations resumed ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers in California and Idaho prepared to join counterparts in
Michigan, Ohio, Montana and Illinois on the picket line Tuesday in
strikes affecting 135,000 students.
   A Montana school district planned to reopen schools Tuesday with
substitute teachers for 12,500 students, and teachers in another
Montana district with 1,900 students planned to go back to work
after accepting a contract offer.
   Labor Day negotiations with a mediator appeared unlikely to avert
a strike by 2,500 teachers of 43,000 students in Sacramento, Calif.,
but officials of the Sacramento City Unified School District said
schools would open Tuesday with heightened security and substitute
teachers.
   ``It doesn't seem there's very much hope of a settlement at this
point,'' Pat Walden, president of Sacramento City Teachers
Association, said Monday. Issues included pay raises, class size and
hiring deadlines for new teachers.
   Also in California, 1,500 San Jose teachers were set to strike at
40 public schools on opening day Tuesday. School officials were
hiring substitutes and monitors for 29,000 students but on Friday
advised parents to plan for child care ``just in case a regular
instructional program is not possible.''
   The district broke off negotiations Saturday with the teachers,
who have been without a contract for 14 months. The district had
offered a 6 percent wage increase this year with a 1 percent bonus;
teachers demanded 10 percent this year and a retroactive raise of 6
percent for last year.
   In Coeur D'Alene, Idaho, 270 of 312 teachers have voted to strike
Tuesday, though officials said they would to keep schools open for
6,800 students. The teachers want a 4.2 percent increase in wages
and benefits; the district has offered 1 percent.
   State Schools Superintendent Jerry Evans said teachers have no
legal right to strike in Idaho, but courts have been reluctant to
order them back to work.
   Schools in the Great Falls school district in Montana were
scheduled to reopen Tuesday with 540 substitute teachers for 12,500
students. Only 45 of 723 teachers showed up for work there last
week. Salaries top the list of several unresolved contract issues;
School Superintendent Larry Williams and Gene Lemelin, president of
the local teachers' union, said no talks were scheduled.
   Laurel, Mont., teachers voted Saturday to accept a contract
giving them a 2.5 percent raise. The 104 teachers, who had said they
were locked out of the schools last week, were to return to their
1,900 students Tuesday.
   In Michigan, 1,010 teachers in Wayne County's Livonia school
district voted late Monday to strike, said Steve Naumcheff,
president of the Michigan Education Association local. Classes were
to begin Tuesday for 15,815 students.
   Teachers in five other Michigan school districts were on strike
last week, affecting more than 15,000 students. The 149 teachers in
the Mount Morris district voted Monday night on a tentative contract
agreement, but classes for nearly 3,500 students would not resume
before Wednesday.
   Negotiations resumed Monday night in two other Michigan
districts, Ferndale, with 310 teachers and 6,000 students, and
Cheboygan, with 120 teachers and 2,400 students.
   In Ohio, no negotiations were held in the Indian Creek and Warren
school districts, and 730 teachers remained off the job, affecting
11,000 students.
   Schools were to remain shut Tuesday in three school districts in
Pennsylvania, said Joy Conley, director of the Pennsylvania State
Education Association's Midwest Region. The strikes affect 474
teachers and nearly 7,900 students.
   Negotiators worked Labor Day to try to end a week-old strike by
350 teachers in Quincy, Ill., that extended summer vacation for
6,800 students. But classes were not likely to resume Tuesday, when
the school board would meet to consider the teachers' counteroffer.
   The bargaining session Monday with a federal mediator was the
first since Aug. 27, when the school board submitted its last offer.
The next day, teachers voted to strike. Pay was the key issue.
</TEXT>
