<DOCNO> AP890904-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 2316EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Suriname     09-04 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suriname,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Urges Dialogue With Amerindian Insurgents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Monday called for a
dialogue with Amerindian insurgents who hijacked a ferryboat, a
small plane and a barge to protest a government peace accord with
Bush Negro guerrillas.
   The Amerindian revolt appeared limited to four villages near the
Dutch-speaking nation's western border with Guyana.
   The National Assembly Monday voted to support ``the government's
efforts to realize peace'' and authorized President Ramsewak Shankar
to hold talks with the Amerindian insurgents.
   An unidentified Amerindian rebel leader said on state television
Sunday night that the uprising was to protest the government's peace
agreement with guerrilla leader Ronny Brunswijk's Jungle Commando.
   The attacks began Friday, shortly after the National Assembly
voted to approve the peace accord.
   Under the terms of the accord, Brunswijk's estimated 200 to 400
men will become a special police force in eastern Suriname where
they operate and where many Amerindians live.
   The Amerindians, allied to the army during the three-year
guerrilla war, fear retribution if they fall under the control of
Brunswijk's men.
   The army also has opposed turning the guerrillas into a police
force.
   Army Commander and strongman Desi Bouterse said Monday the
Amerindian insurgents have ``captured a large amount of supplies and
appear to be well armed. They also have a foreign connection.''
   He said they were receiving funds from supporters in Holland.
   On Sunday, Amerindian gunmen hijacked a rice barge with three
crewmen and occupied a major sluice on the Nickerie River, which
provides irrigation to a large rice-growing area in western
Suriname, the daily De Ware Tyd said Monday.
   Armed Amerindians shot and killed one passenger when they
hijacked a ferryboat about 30 miles west of Paramaribo Friday. An
unspecified number of passengers were still being held Monday.
   The hijackers were also still holding a small aircraft and its
pilot, captured on Friday.
   The Amerindian leader who spoke on state television said hostages
would not be harmed.
   Vice President Henck Arron said the peace accord was explained to
the population over state radio ``in eight languages, including Bush
Negro and Amerindian dialects.''
   He said it does not provide for control of Amerindian communities
by Brunswijk's men.
   The 65,000 Bush Negroes _ descendents of escaped African slaves _
and 10,000 Amerindians are traditional rivals. They compete for land
for farming, hunting and fishing.
   Suriname gained independence from Holland in 1975.
</TEXT>
