<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Ambassador     09-04 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Ambassador,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0678 to restore Honduras to dateline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Honduran Ambassador Says U.S. Treats Him Like Slave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Honduran ambassador to
Panama who is now imprisoned in Miami for importing cocaine said he
is being treated like a slave by prison officials.
   Col. Rigoberto Regalado Lara made the accusation in a telephone
interview with the Tegucigalpa newspaper La Tribunta that was
published Sunday.
   It quoted Regalado Lara as saying:
   ``Although I have been a friend of the United States during my 20
years as a Honduran army official, studying in U.S. schools, and
participating in U.S.-Honduran joint military maneuvers ... now the
North Americans have shackled and chained me in jail, and they have
treated me like a slave of the Spanish colonial period.''
   Regalado Lara, 51, was arrested in Miami on May 15, 1988, and
police said they found about 50 pounds of cocaine hidden in his
suitcase. He was convicted of importing cocaine and sentenced to 10
years in prison.
   The Honduran army discharged Regalado Lara immediately after his
arrest and the Honduran government did not intervene on behalf of
the former commander of the Honduran First Infantry Batallion.
   ``They have left me on my own,'' he said of Honduran officials.
   He was quoted as saying, ``I wish that in Honduras we could do
the same with U.S. soldiers who break the law. In my country they
open the prison doors for the North Americans to go free without
judgment.''
</TEXT>
