<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 2327EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Japan     09-04 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Japan,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Kaifu Says Debt Problem Requires Collaboration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TALLI NAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Toshiki Kaifu of Japan met President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari on Monday night and declared that debtors
and creditors must closely collaborate if they ever hope to solve
the foreign debt problems of developing nations.
   Kaifu arrived Monday for a two-day visit, during which he is
expected to announce the January release of the first half of a $2
billion loan Japan has pledged to Mexico under the Brady Plan for
debt relief in developing countries.
   The plan is named for U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, who
proposed it.
   The Japanese loan would be used with funds from the International
Monetary Fund and World Bank in programs to reduce Mexico's $107
billion foreign debt.
   The prime minister's visit follows a July agreement between
Mexico and foreign creditor banks to reduce $53 billion of the debt.
   Kaifu is also expected to formalize Japan's offer of $1.2 billion
in aid for pollution control in Mexico City.
   Some of the money will be used for electric trains to ease
traffic congestion and cut smog, said Mario Moya Palencia, Mexico's
ambassador to Japan.
   Kaifu said in a written statement, released when his plane landed
in Mexico City: ``The problem of the accumulated foreign debt cannot
be solved, if close collaboration between the parties involved _
that is, the debtor and creditor countries _ is not achieved.''
   He said, ``My country and the region to which Mexico belongs can
take advantage of this occasion to reaffirm their mutual political
will to continue contributing to the peace, stability and
development of all countries of the world.''
   Mexico has said arrangements will be made while Kaifu is in
Mexico for a reciprocal visit by Salinas to Japan.
   Japanese investment here _ $1.5 billion is in about 200 companies
_ accounts for 6 percent of all foreign investment in Mexico.
   Japan is Mexico's second-largest trading partner after the United
States. Trade last year between the two countries was $3.4 billion,
according to Mexican government figures.
   Mexico sells Japan food, chemicals and petroleum. It buys mostly
manufactured products.
   Kaifu, who took office last month, arrived in Mexico from Boston.
He leaves for Canada on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
