<SECOND>BC-History, Adv11,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Sept. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, Sept. 11, the 254th day of 1989. There are 111
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Two hundred years ago, on Sept. 11, 1789, Alexander Hamilton was
appointed the first U.S. Secretary of the Treasury.
   On this date:
   In 1777, during the American Revolution, forces under Gen. George
Washington suffered defeat at the hands of the British in the Battle
of Brandywine near Wilmington, Del.
   In 1814, an American fleet scored a decisive victory over the
British in the Battle of Lake Champlain in the War of 1812.
   In 1850, ``Swedish Nightingale'' Jenny Lind gave her first
concert in the United States, at Castle Garden, N.Y.
   In 1885, author D.H. Lawrence was born in Eastwood, England.
   In 1936, President Franklin D. Roosevelt dedicated Boulder Dam _
now known as Hoover Dam _ by pressing a key in Washington to signal
the startup of the dam's first hydroelectric generator in Nevada.
   In 1941, speaking in Des Moines, Iowa, Charles A. Lindbergh
charged that ``the British, the Jewish and the Roosevelt
administration'' were trying to involve the United States in World
War II.
   In 1944, President Franklin D. Roosevelt and British Prime
Minister Winston Churchill met in Canada at the second Quebec
Conference.
   In 1949, the New York Yankees got 11 bases on balls during a
12-run third inning of a home game against the Washington Senators.
(Final score: Yankees 20, Senators 5.)
   In 1971, former Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev died of a heart
attack at the age of 77.
   In 1973, Chile's President, Salvador Allende, died in a violent
military coup that overthrew his government.
   In 1978, Georgi Markov, a Bulgarian defector, died at a British
hospital four days after he was stabbed by a man wielding a poisoned
umbrella tip.
   In 1982, 46 people were killed in a U.S. Army helicopter crash
near Mannheim, West Germany.
   In 1985, Pete Rose of the Cincinnati Reds cracked career hit
number 4,192 off Eric Show of the San Diego Padres, eclipsing the
record held by Ty Cobb.
   Ten years ago: President Carter asked Congress for an additional
$4.7 billion dollars for Pentagon spending in fiscal year 1980.
   Five years ago: President Reagan announced he would meet with
Soviet Foreign Minister Andrei Gromyko at the White House on Sept.
28. Hurricane Diana slammed into North Carolina's southeastern coast
with winds clocked at 100 mph.
   One year ago: Mats Wilander of Sweden won the men's U.S. Open
title in New York.
   Today's Birthdays: Former Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
is 72. Former Dallas Cowboys football coach Tom Landry is 65. Actor
Earl Holliman is 61. Senator Bob Packwood, R-Ore., is 57. Movie
director Brian De Palma is 49.
   Thought for Today: ``When the gods are angry with a man, they
give him what he asks for.'' _ Greek saying.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Use Monday, Sept. 11</NOTE>
