<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks     09-04 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher on Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose Monday on London's stock
exchange, boosted by takeover speculation that pushed the key FT-SE
100 Share Index higher for yet another session.
   Continued talk of potential takeovers was cited as the primary
factor in the market's continued rise above the psychologically
important 2,400-point level.
   ``The market is still afraid of selling,'' a dealer with a large
European institution said, ``as long as this takeover talk remains
active.''
   The FT-SE 100 closed at 2,419.2, up 11.7 points, or 0.05 percent,
but off from its high for the day of 2,424.5. The high was
established during a late-morning runup sparked by news of Bowater
Industries' 382 million-pound, or $592 million, bid for specialty
printer Norton Opax.
   Norton Opax subsequently rejected the bid. Bowater, which hasn't
commented on Norton's rejection, bid t increase its current 26
percent Norton stake in an effort to short circuit the company's
move to acquire De La Rue Co., another specialty printing concern,
for 484 million pounds, or $750.2 million.
   Volume on the London market was substantially below the level
Friday, when the FT-SE 100 closed above the 2,400-point level. On
Monday, only 369.9 million shares were traded, down from 533.0
million Friday.
   The narrow FT-SE 30 Share Index closed firmer as well at 2,003.6,
up 10.9 points. The FT-500 index was up 6.96 at 1,351.10.
</TEXT>
