<DOCNO> AP890904-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 1950EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-ConsumerConfidence     09-04 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Confidence,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll: Consumer Confidence Declined In August</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer confidence dropped in August after
rising steadily for several months, according to a poll released
today by a business group.
   The Conference Board's Consumer Confidence Index declined in
August to 114.7, a loss of almost six points for the month, the
group said.
   A substantial share of the decline reflects consumers' somewhat
less positive assessment of current economic conditions, the group
said. Expectations for the future are down moderately, while buying
plans are mixed, it said.
   Consumer confidence is important because of its impact on
consumer spending, which drives about two-thirds of domestic
economic activity.
   ``Although the level of consumer confidence is down, it is still,
in the context of the survey's history, reassuringly strong,'' said
Fabian Linden, executive director of the Conference Board's Consumer
Research Center.
   ``While one month is too brief a period on which to make a
long-term judgment, the magnitude of this month's decline cannot be
dismissed as inconsequential,'' he said in a statement. ``We must
wait for at least another month to see whether this is the beginning
of a trend.''
   Only 27 percent of survey participants said that current economic
conditions are good, down from 31.6 percent a month earlier. About
31 percent said they believed jobs were plentiful, down from about
33 percent in July.
   There was a modest decline, from 18.6 percent to 17.2 percent, in
the number who expect more jobs to become available over the next
six months. About 25 percent of respondents believed that their
families' financial situation would improve, a drop of about 2
percent points from July.
   Automobile purchasing plans remained unchanged at 7.1 percent of
respondents. The percentage planning to buy a home declined to 3.5
percent from 3.7 percent in July. Interest in buying a major
appliance dropped to 27.1 percent from 30.5 percent.
   The monthly survey, covering 5,000 U.S. households, is conducted
for the New York-based group by National Family Opinion of Toledo,
Ohio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
